"""AP History: 9 units matching curriculum"""

def P(q,ex,a,diff): return {"q":q,"ex":ex,"a":a,"diff":diff}
def T(title,problems): return {"title":title,"problems":problems}

AP_HISTORY = [
  # Unit 1 — APUSH
  [
    T("Colonial Foundations",[
      P("What were the key differences between New England, Middle, and Southern colonies?","Think economy, religion, society.","New England: Puritan communities, subsistence farming, town meetings, fishing/trade. Middle: diverse religions, mixed economy, breadbasket colonies (wheat). Southern: plantation economy, cash crops (tobacco, rice, indigo), reliance on indentured servants then enslaved labor. All differed in demographics, labor systems, and relationship with Indigenous peoples.","medium"),
      P("What was the Columbian Exchange and what were its consequences?","Think biological and cultural transfers.","The Columbian Exchange: transfer of plants, animals, diseases, and people between Americas and Old World after 1492. Consequences: European diseases devastated Indigenous populations (90%+ mortality in some regions); American crops (potatoes, corn, tomatoes) transformed European diets; horses transformed Plains Indigenous cultures; enslaved Africans brought to Americas; sugar, tobacco, cotton became global commodities.","medium"),
      P("How did the Great Awakening shape colonial society and politics?","Think religion and democratization.","First Great Awakening (1730s–40s): evangelical revival led by Edwards, Whitefield. Challenged established church authority; emphasized personal conversion experience; created new denominations; fostered democratic impulse (direct relationship with God without clergy mediation); contributed to cross-colonial communication; indirectly prepared colonists to question political authority.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Revolution and Founding",[
      P("What were the main arguments in Common Sense (1776) and why was it influential?","Think Paine's argument against monarchy.","Paine argued: monarchy is irrational and hereditary privilege unjust; Britain exploits colonies economically; America's destiny is to be a republic and asylum for liberty; independence is practical and possible. Influential because: written in plain language accessible to all; framed independence as a matter of reason, not just grievance; gave colonists a positive vision, not just a list of complaints.","medium"),
      P("What were the key compromises at the Constitutional Convention of 1787?","Think representation, slavery, executive power.","Major compromises: (1) Great Compromise: bicameral legislature — Senate (equal state representation) + House (proportional by population); (2) Three-Fifths Compromise: enslaved persons counted as 3/5 for representation and taxation; (3) Commerce/Slave Trade Compromise: Congress could not ban slave importation until 1808; (4) Electoral College: indirect election of president. Each resolved disputes between large/small states and between North and South.","hard"),
      P("What were the main debates between Federalists and Anti-Federalists?","Think ratification debates.","Federalists (Hamilton, Madison, Jay): strong central government needed for stability, commerce, national defense; Constitution includes checks and balances protecting liberty. Anti-Federalists (Patrick Henry, Mason): feared tyranny from distant central government; demanded Bill of Rights; preferred power in states closer to the people. The debates produced The Federalist Papers and ultimately a Bill of Rights as condition for ratification.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Early Republic and Expansion",[
      P("What was the significance of Marbury v. Madison (1803)?","Think judicial review.","Marbury v. Madison established judicial review — the Supreme Court's power to strike down laws that violate the Constitution. Chief Justice Marshall ruled that the Court could not compel Madison to deliver Marbury's commission (limiting Court's original jurisdiction) but asserted the Court's power to interpret the Constitution. This fundamentally shaped American government by making the judiciary a co-equal branch capable of checking Congress and the President.","medium"),
      P("How did Manifest Destiny shape US expansion and conflict in the 19th century?","Think ideology, territory, and consequences.","Manifest Destiny: belief that US expansion across the continent was divinely ordained and inevitable. Led to: Indian Removal Act (1830) and Trail of Tears; Mexican-American War (1846–48) gaining California and Southwest; Oregon Territory settlement with Britain; Gadsden Purchase. Consequences: continental empire achieved; debate over slavery in new territories intensified sectional conflict; Indigenous peoples dispossessed and removed.","medium"),
      P("What caused the rise of Jacksonian Democracy and what did it change?","Think expanded suffrage and populism.","Jackson represented the 'common man' — expanded white male suffrage (property requirements dropped), spoils system (rewarding political supporters with government jobs), Indian Removal, opposition to Bank of the US (seen as elite privilege), nullification crisis. Jacksonian Democracy broadened democratic participation for white men while simultaneously intensifying oppression of Indigenous peoples and enslaved Americans.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Sectionalism and Civil War",[
      P("How did slavery cause increasing sectional tension between 1820 and 1860?","Think Missouri Compromise, Compromise of 1850, Kansas-Nebraska Act.","Sequence: Missouri Compromise (1820) — Missouri slave, Maine free, 36°30' line. Compromise of 1850 — California free, popular sovereignty in territories, stronger Fugitive Slave Act. Kansas-Nebraska Act (1854) — repealed Missouri Compromise, popular sovereignty → 'Bleeding Kansas.' Dred Scott (1857) — ruled Congress cannot prohibit slavery anywhere. Each compromise failed; sectional crisis deepened until Lincoln's election triggered secession.","hard"),
      P("What military and political factors determined the Union's victory in the Civil War?","Think resources, leadership, and strategy.","Union advantages: larger population, greater industrial capacity, railroad network, naval blockade. Confederate advantages: defensive fighting, experienced officers, high motivation. Turning points: Antietam (1862) — allowed Lincoln to issue Emancipation Proclamation, changing war aims; Gettysburg and Vicksburg (1863) — Confederacy loses offensive capability and Mississippi River. Emancipation: transformed war into fight for freedom; 180,000 Black soldiers joined Union Army; Britain and France declined to recognize Confederacy.","hard"),
      P("What were Lincoln's key arguments in the Gettysburg Address?","Think democratic ideals and war purpose.","Lincoln reframed the Civil War: not merely to preserve the Union but to fulfill the promise of the Declaration of Independence — 'all men are created equal.' He honored the fallen by insisting their deaths must advance the 'new birth of freedom.' He also asserted that government 'of the people, by the people, for the people' must not perish — connecting democratic self-government to the war's outcome.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Reconstruction",[
      P("What were the goals and achievements of Radical Reconstruction?","Think 13th, 14th, 15th Amendments and freedmen's gains.","Goals: integrate formerly enslaved people as citizens, reconstruct Southern society, punish Confederate leadership. Achievements: 13th Amendment (abolished slavery), 14th Amendment (birthright citizenship, equal protection), 15th Amendment (Black male suffrage), Freedmen's Bureau (education, labor contracts), Black political participation (Black congressmen, state officials). Ended by: Compromise of 1877 withdrew federal troops; Redeemer Democrats used violence and disenfranchisement to restore white supremacy.","hard"),
      P("How did sharecropping perpetuate economic dependence for formerly enslaved people?","Think labor system and debt cycle.","After slavery, Southern planters needed labor; freedpeople needed land and income. Sharecropping: freedpeople farmed land in exchange for a share of the crop. In practice: planters controlled crop accounting; high interest on supplies from company stores; debt peonage trapped families in multi-year cycles. Sharecropping effectively recreated economic bondage without legal ownership — freedpeople had legal freedom but limited economic independence.","medium"),
      P("What is the 'Lost Cause' narrative and how did it distort Civil War history?","Think myth-making and its consequences.","Lost Cause: post-war Southern mythology reframing the Confederacy as a noble cause fighting for 'states' rights' rather than slavery; portraying Confederate leaders as honorable; depicting enslaved people as content. Consequences: justified Jim Crow; Confederate monuments erected to intimidate Black communities; erased slavery as cause of the war from textbooks. Historians today reject Lost Cause as factually false — Confederate secession documents explicitly name slavery as the cause.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Industrialization and the Gilded Age",[
      P("What factors drove American industrialization after the Civil War?","Think resources, technology, labor, capital.","Key factors: abundant natural resources (coal, iron, oil); railroads linking national market; wave of immigration providing labor; technological innovation (steel production, electricity); capital from banks and investors; government support (land grants, tariffs, laissez-faire policy). Robber barons (Carnegie, Rockefeller, Morgan) built industrial empires through vertical/horizontal integration and monopolistic practices.","medium"),
      P("What were the goals and methods of the Populist movement?","Think agrarian grievances and political demands.","Populists: farmers facing falling crop prices, railroad price-gouging, debt burden. Demands: graduated income tax, direct election of senators, government ownership of railroads, silver coinage (inflate currency to ease debt). Formed People's Party (1892). Significance: first major third-party challenge; many Populist demands later enacted in Progressive Era; demonstrated farmers' political power and limits of two-party system for reform.","medium"),
      P("How did Social Darwinism justify inequality in the Gilded Age?","Think ideology and its critics.","Social Darwinism: applied Darwin's natural selection to society — wealthy succeeded because they were naturally superior; poverty resulted from personal weakness; government intervention in the economy was unnatural interference. Used to justify: laissez-faire capitalism, opposition to labor regulations, imperialism (stronger nations dominate weaker). Critics (settlement house workers, progressive reformers, labor organizers) argued poverty was structural, not personal — caused by industrial conditions, not individual failure.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Progressive Era and WWI",[
      P("What were the major reforms of the Progressive Era?","Think political, economic, and social reform.","Progressive Era (1890s–1920): Muckrakers exposed corruption and corporate abuse (Upton Sinclair, Ida Tarbell). Political reforms: direct election of senators (17th Amendment), initiative/referendum/recall, primary elections, women's suffrage (19th Amendment, 1920). Economic reforms: Sherman Antitrust Act enforcement, Pure Food and Drug Act, Federal Reserve. Social reform: settlement houses (Jane Addams), child labor laws, temperance. Progressivism was mostly for white Americans — limited benefits for Black Americans, who faced intensifying segregation.","hard"),
      P("What were the causes and consequences of US entry into WWI?","Think neutrality, Lusitania, Zimmermann Telegram.","Causes of US entry (1917): German unrestricted submarine warfare (sinking of Lusitania, 1915); Zimmermann Telegram (Germany proposing Mexican alliance against US); Wilson's idealism ('make the world safe for democracy'). Consequences: Selective Service drafted 3 million; War Industries Board mobilized economy; Committee on Public Information waged propaganda; Espionage/Sedition Acts suppressed dissent; Great Migration of Black Americans North accelerated; US emerged as global power; Senate rejected League of Nations.","hard"),
      P("Why did the Senate reject the League of Nations?","Think reservationists vs. irreconcilables.","Wilson proposed the League of Nations (Article X required members to defend each other's sovereignty) as central to the Versailles Treaty. Senate opposition: Irreconcilables (Borah, Johnson) opposed any international organization; Reservationists (Lodge) demanded amendments limiting US obligations. Wilson refused compromise and suffered a stroke during speaking tour. Senate rejected the treaty — the US never joined. Consequence: League weakened; US returned to semi-isolationism; future collective security mechanisms lacked US support.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Depression, New Deal, WWII",[
      P("What caused the Great Depression and how did Hoover's response fail?","Think stock crash, banking collapse, policy errors.","Causes: stock market speculation and crash (1929); banking panics and collapse (9,000 banks failed); Smoot-Hawley Tariff worsened global trade; Federal Reserve raised interest rates (contractionary). Hoover's response: believed in voluntarism and limited federal role; opposed direct relief as 'the dole' that undermined character; Reconstruction Finance Corporation too small, too late. Result: unemployment hit 25%; Hoovervilles formed; Bonus Army dispersed by military.","hard"),
      P("What were the key programs of the New Deal and what debate surrounds its legacy?","Think relief, recovery, reform.","New Deal: Relief (FERA, CCC — direct aid and jobs), Recovery (AAA — farm prices, NRA — industrial codes), Reform (Social Security, SEC, FDIC, Wagner Act — unions). Legacy debate: Keynesians argue it worked but wasn't big enough; conservatives argue it prolonged Depression through regulation and uncertainty; historians note it excluded many Black Americans (discriminatory application), agricultural workers, and domestic workers. WWII spending — not the New Deal — ended the Depression.","hard"),
      P("What was the significance of the home front during WWII?","Think production, labor, and civil rights tensions.","Home front: War Production Board converted industry to war production — Arsenal of Democracy; women entered workforce ('Rosie the Riveter'); rationing and war bonds. Double V Campaign: Black Americans fought for victory abroad and democracy at home; A. Philip Randolph threatened March on Washington → FDR signed Executive Order 8802 banning defense industry discrimination. Japanese American internment (Executive Order 9066): 120,000 incarcerated — Korematsu v. US upheld it (later repudiated). War accelerated urbanization and migration.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Cold War and Civil Rights",[
      P("What were the key strategies of US containment policy during the Cold War?","Think Truman Doctrine, Marshall Plan, NATO, Korea, Vietnam.","Containment (Kennan): prevent Soviet expansion without direct war. Truman Doctrine (1947): aid to Greece and Turkey. Marshall Plan (1948): $13B to rebuild Western Europe (prevent communism through prosperity). NATO (1949): collective defense alliance. Korean War (1950–53): defended South Korea; ended in stalemate at 38th parallel. Vietnam: escalated from Eisenhower through Nixon; 58,000 US dead; credibility trap; Tet Offensive undermined public support; ended in communist victory (1975).","hard"),
      P("What were the key phases and strategies of the Civil Rights Movement?","Think litigation, nonviolent direct action, legislation.","Legal phase: NAACP litigation → Brown v. Board of Education (1954) overturned 'separate but equal.' Direct action: Montgomery Bus Boycott (1955–56), sit-ins (Greensboro), Freedom Rides, Birmingham Campaign (Bull Connor's brutality), March on Washington (1963). Legislative victories: Civil Rights Act (1964) — banned discrimination in public accommodations and employment; Voting Rights Act (1965) — protected Black suffrage; Fair Housing Act (1968). Later phase: Black Power, urban uprisings, King's assassination (1968).","hard"),
      P("How did the Reagan Revolution change American politics?","Think conservative ideology and policy.","Reagan's coalition: disaffected white working-class voters, evangelical Christians, business conservatives, Sun Belt growth. Policies: supply-side economics ('Reaganomics') — tax cuts (especially top rates), deregulation, reduced domestic spending; military buildup; Strategic Defense Initiative; strong anti-Soviet rhetoric. Results: income inequality increased; deregulation contributed to S&L crisis; Cold War ended (debate over Reagan's role vs. Soviet internal collapse). Legacy: shifted Democratic Party rightward; 'government is the problem' became dominant political frame.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Contemporary America",[
      P("What were the causes and consequences of the 9/11 attacks?","Think terrorism, policy response, and civil liberties.","Causes: Al-Qaeda extremism, US Middle East policy (Gulf War stationing troops in Saudi Arabia, support for Israel, Iraq sanctions). Consequences: USA PATRIOT Act (surveillance expansion); Department of Homeland Security; Afghanistan War (2001 — Taliban removed, then prolonged occupation); Iraq War (2003 — WMD claims proved false; Hussein removed; destabilized region); NSA mass surveillance; debate over torture and detainee rights (Guantanamo). Long-term: over 7,000 US military dead; trillions spent; ISIS emerged from Iraq War aftermath.","hard"),
      P("How has economic inequality changed in America since the 1970s?","Think wages, wealth gap, and policy debates.","Since 1970s: top 1% share of income roughly tripled; real wages for median workers stagnated despite productivity growth; union membership fell from 35% to ~10%; wealth gap between white and Black Americans persists. Causes debated: globalization (manufacturing jobs offshore), technology (automation), financialization, tax policy (capital gains vs. labor income), declining union power, deregulation. Policy debates: minimum wage, progressive taxation, healthcare access, education costs.","medium"),
      P("What themes connect major turning points in US history?","Think recurring tensions.","Recurring tensions: (1) Liberty vs. equality — freedom for whom? (slavery, civil rights, gender equality); (2) Federal vs. state power — nullification, New Deal, civil rights enforcement; (3) Isolationism vs. global engagement — Monroe Doctrine through WWI neutrality through Cold War; (4) Economic opportunity vs. inequality — Gilded Age, Progressive Era, New Deal, Reagan; (5) National security vs. civil liberties — Alien & Sedition Acts, WWII internment, PATRIOT Act. APUSH recognizes these tensions run throughout American history.","medium"),
    ]),
  ],
  # Unit 2 — AP World History: Modern
  [
    T("Global Tapestry (1200–1450)",[
      P("What were the key characteristics of the major empires and states in 1200–1450?","Think Mongols, Mali, Song China, Byzantine, Islamic caliphates.","Song China: commercial revolution, printing, gunpowder, paper money, Confucian bureaucracy. Mongol Empire: largest contiguous land empire; facilitated Silk Road trade (Pax Mongolica); spread plague. Mali Empire: controlled trans-Saharan gold-salt trade; Mansa Musa's hajj showcased wealth. Byzantine: declining but preserved Greco-Roman knowledge. Islamic caliphates: fragmented but culturally dynamic — House of Wisdom, algebra, astronomy. Key theme: diverse but interconnected world through trade networks.","hard"),
      P("What was the significance of the Silk Roads and Indian Ocean trade networks?","Think goods, ideas, and disease.","Silk Roads (overland): connected China to Mediterranean; traded silk, spices, paper, gunpowder, disease, religion. Indian Ocean trade: dominated by Arab, Indian, Swahili, and Chinese merchants; monsoon winds enabled reliable navigation; traded cotton, spices, gold, enslaved people. Both networks transmitted: Buddhism, Islam, Christianity; technological innovations; the Black Death (1340s). Key: trade routes moved more than goods — they spread religions, technologies, and pathogens.","medium"),
      P("How did Islam spread and consolidate across diverse regions by 1450?","Think trade, conquest, and Sufism.","Islam spread through: Arab conquests (622–750 CE) — Middle East, North Africa, Iberian Peninsula; trade routes — Indian Ocean merchants brought Islam to East Africa, South Asia, Southeast Asia; Sufi missionaries adapted to local cultures. By 1450: Islam united diverse peoples through shared law (sharia), pilgrimage (hajj), and language (Arabic for scholarship). Mongol conversions added Central Asian Muslims. Key tension: unity of umma vs. diversity of practice across regions.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Networks of Exchange (1200–1450)",[
      P("What was the Black Death and what were its consequences?","Think demographic collapse and social change.","Black Death (bubonic plague, 1347–51): killed 30–50% of Europe's population; also devastated Middle East and Central Asia. Consequences: labor shortages → higher wages for survivors (weakened serfdom); Church authority questioned (prayer failed); Jewish communities scapegoated and massacred; trade disruption; eventually stimulated technological innovation and individualism (Renaissance). Demonstrates how disease traveled trade networks.","medium"),
      P("What role did the Mongol Empire play in connecting Eurasia?","Think Pax Mongolica and its limits.","Pax Mongolica (Mongol Peace, 1200s–1300s): Mongol control of overland routes → relatively safe travel across Eurasia; Marco Polo, Ibn Battuta, and diplomatic missions traveled these routes; silk, spices, and plague all moved more freely. Limits: Mongols were destructive conquerors (Baghdad sacked 1258, Abbasid Caliphate destroyed); eventually fragmented into four khanates that sometimes warred. Legacy: connected Eurasia more thoroughly than ever before — but also spread Black Death.","medium"),
      P("How did the Indian Ocean trade network differ from Mediterranean or Silk Road trade?","Think maritime technology and merchant communities.","Indian Ocean: relied on monsoon wind systems — seasonal, predictable; enabled larger ships carrying bulk cargo. Merchants: Arab dhow captains, Indian Gujarati merchants, Swahili city-state traders, Chinese junks under Zheng He. Commodities: spices (pepper, cloves, nutmeg), cotton textiles, gold, enslaved people. Key difference: largely peaceful commercial exchange (not state-controlled); created cosmopolitan port cities (Calicut, Malacca, Kilwa) with diverse merchant communities. Religion (Islam) often followed trade routes.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Land-Based Empires (1450–1750)",[
      P("What were the Gunpowder Empires and what common features did they share?","Think Ottoman, Safavid, Mughal.","Gunpowder Empires: Ottoman (Turkey), Safavid (Persia/Iran), Mughal (India). Common features: used gunpowder weapons to conquer and maintain large territories; ruled diverse populations; patronized arts and architecture (Topkapi, Isfahan, Taj Mahal); relied on professional armies; faced challenge of integrating diverse religions. Key differences: Ottoman — Sunni Islam, ruled Christians and Jews through millet system; Safavid — Shia Islam, conflict with Ottomans; Mughal — Muslim rulers over majority Hindu population; Akbar promoted religious tolerance.","hard"),
      P("How did the Ottoman Empire maintain control over diverse populations?","Think millet system and administrative tools.","Ottoman administration: Sultan → Grand Vizier → regional governors. Millet system: non-Muslim communities (Greek Orthodox, Armenian, Jewish) governed their own religious affairs under their own leaders; paid jizya (non-Muslim tax) in exchange for protection. Devshirme: recruited Christian boys to train as elite Janissary soldiers and administrators — meritocratic in theory. Geographic position: Istanbul controlled routes between Europe and Asia, generating trade revenue. Weakened after 17th century through military defeats and administrative corruption.","medium"),
      P("How did the Ming Dynasty attempt to control its borders and project power?","Think Great Wall, Zheng He, and isolationism.","Ming China (1368–1644): rebuilt and extended the Great Wall against Mongol threats; Zheng He's voyages (1405–1433) — 7 massive naval expeditions to Southeast Asia, India, Arabia, East Africa; demonstrated Chinese wealth and sought tribute relationships. Then reversed: Confucian officials opposed costly maritime expeditions; China turned inward; banned private foreign trade (isolationism). Consequence: withdrew from maritime dominance just as Europeans were entering Indian Ocean — left vacuum that Portuguese and Dutch filled.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Transoceanic Interconnections (1450–1750)",[
      P("What drove European exploration and what were its consequences?","Think technology, motives, and impact.","Motives: desire for direct access to Asian spices (cut out Arab/Ottoman middlemen); missionary zeal; competition between European states; printing press spread geographic knowledge; compass and caravel enabled open-ocean sailing. Portuguese: coastal Africa → India. Spanish: Columbus → Americas. Consequences: Columbian Exchange; Atlantic slave trade; destruction of Indigenous empires; silver from Americas inflated European prices (Price Revolution); created truly global trade network for first time.","medium"),
      P("What was the encomienda system and how did it affect Indigenous peoples?","Think Spanish colonial labor exploitation.","Encomienda: Spanish Crown granted conquistadors rights to labor from Indigenous people in exchange for their 'protection' and religious instruction. In practice: forced labor in silver mines (Potosí) and on plantations; brutal conditions; combined with disease to devastate Indigenous populations (90%+ decline in some regions). Las Casas documented abuses and advocated for Indigenous rights → led to New Laws (1542) attempting to reform — largely unenforced. Eventually replaced by mita (forced labor drafts) as Indigenous population collapsed.","hard"),
      P("How did the Atlantic slave trade reshape Africa, the Americas, and Europe?","Think scale, demographics, and economic impact.","Scale: 12+ million Africans transported to Americas (1500–1900); millions more died in middle passage or capture. African impact: demographic loss of working-age adults; destabilized West African states; some African kingdoms profited from slave trade. Americas: enslaved African labor built plantation economies (sugar, tobacco, cotton); African cultures transformed American culture (music, language, religion). European impact: plantation profits funded industrialization; triangular trade (manufactured goods → Africa → enslaved people → Americas → raw materials → Europe) enriched European merchants. Created the 'Black Atlantic' diaspora.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Revolutions (1750–1900)",[
      P("What were the causes and global impact of the Atlantic Revolutions?","Think American, French, Haitian, Latin American.","Atlantic Revolutions: American (1776) — Enlightenment ideals, colonial grievances, republican government. French (1789) — fiscal crisis, social inequality, Enlightenment ideas; radical phase produced Terror; Napoleon spread revolutionary ideas across Europe. Haitian (1791–1804) — enslaved people applied universal rights to themselves; only successful slave revolution in history; terrified slaveholding societies. Latin American (1810s–20s) — Creole elites led independence from Spain/Portugal, inspired by Enlightenment and Atlantic precedents. Common thread: Enlightenment ideas of rights, sovereignty, and equality.","hard"),
      P("What caused industrialization in Britain and how did it spread?","Think conditions and diffusion.","British advantages: coal and iron deposits; Atlantic trade wealth; parliamentary government protecting property rights; enclosures creating urban labor supply; technological innovation (steam engine, spinning jenny). Spread: Belgium and Germany industrialized next; US industrialization accelerated after Civil War; Japan after Meiji Restoration (1868). Consequences: urbanization, factory system, class conflict, new forms of imperialism enabled by industrial technology.","medium"),
      P("What was the 'New Imperialism' of the 19th century and how did it differ from earlier colonialism?","Think industrial motives and methods.","New Imperialism (1870s–1914): European powers colonized most of Africa and Asia. Motives: raw materials for industry; markets for manufactured goods; investment opportunities; Social Darwinism justified European racial superiority; strategic competition. Methods: industrial weapons (Maxim gun, railroads, steamships) enabled rapid conquest. Key event: Berlin Conference (1884) — European powers divided Africa without African input. Differed from earlier colonialism in: speed, scale, direct administrative control, and industrial-age justifications.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Consequences of Industrialization (1750–1900)",[
      P("How did Karl Marx analyze capitalism and what solutions did he propose?","Think class struggle and communism.","Marx's analysis: capitalism creates two classes — bourgeoisie (owners of means of production) and proletariat (workers who sell labor). Workers exploited through surplus value (paid less than value they create). Alienation: workers disconnected from product, process, and each other. Historical materialism: economic base determines political and cultural superstructure; history moves through class conflict. Solution: proletarian revolution → socialism (workers control state) → communism (classless, stateless society). Das Kapital (1867) provided systematic analysis.","hard"),
      P("What was the women's suffrage movement and how did it connect to other reforms?","Think connections and global scope.","Women's suffrage: Seneca Falls Convention (1848) — Declaration of Sentiments; 19th Amendment (1920) in US; many Western countries granted suffrage 1900s–1920s. Connected to: abolitionism (many suffragists were anti-slavery activists); temperance movement; settlement house work; labor rights. International: New Zealand first (1893), UK 1918, France 1944, Switzerland 1971. Arguments for: equal citizenship, no taxation without representation, women's moral authority. Opposition: threat to family structure, women's 'separate sphere.'","medium"),
      P("How did nationalism reshape political borders in the 19th century?","Think unification and dissolution.","Nationalism: shared language, culture, ethnicity, or history as basis for political community. Italian unification (Risorgimento, 1861): Cavour's diplomacy + Garibaldi's military campaign united peninsula. German unification (1871): Bismarck's 'blood and iron' through wars with Denmark, Austria, France → German Empire. Ottoman dissolution: Balkan nations gained independence (Greece, Serbia, Romania, Bulgaria). Austro-Hungarian tensions: diverse empire struggled to contain nationalist movements. Legacy: nationalist conflicts contributed to WWI.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Global Conflict and its Aftermath (1900–present)",[
      P("What were the causes of WWI?","Think MAIN: militarism, alliances, imperialism, nationalism.","Militarism: European arms race, especially Germany vs. Britain (naval). Alliances: Triple Alliance (Germany, Austria-Hungary, Italy) vs. Triple Entente (France, Russia, Britain) — meant local conflict escalated globally. Imperialism: competition for colonies created tensions. Nationalism: Serbian nationalism threatened Austria-Hungary; assassination of Franz Ferdinand (Sarajevo, 1914) triggered alliance system. Underlying cause: rigid alliance system and mobilization timetables meant assassination led to general European war within weeks.","medium"),
      P("How did decolonization reshape the world after WWII?","Think Asian and African independence movements.","Decolonization: WWII weakened European powers; Atlantic Charter promised self-determination; anticolonial nationalist movements grew. Asia: India (1947, partition into India/Pakistan); Indonesia (1949); Vietnam (fought French then US). Africa: Gold Coast/Ghana (1957) — Kwame Nkrumah; most of Africa independent by 1965; Portugal's colonies 1974–75. Methods: nonviolent (Gandhi's satyagraha), armed struggle (Algeria, Vietnam, Kenya Mau Mau), negotiated transition. Legacy: Cold War superpowers competed for influence in newly independent nations (proxy wars, coups).","hard"),
    ]),
  ],
  # Unit 3 — AP European History
  [
    T("Renaissance and Reformation",[
      P("What were the key ideas of the Renaissance and how did they differ from medieval thought?","Think humanism and secularism.","Renaissance humanism: shifted focus from God and afterlife (medieval) to human potential, achievement, and this world. Secularism: interest in classical Greco-Roman texts, civic virtue, and earthly life. Individual: celebrated individual genius (Leonardo, Michelangelo). Patronage: wealthy merchants and rulers funded art for prestige. Spread: printing press (1450s) disseminated ideas; Italian city-states → Northern Europe. Key figures: Erasmus (Christian humanism), Thomas More, Machiavelli (political realism in The Prince).","medium"),
      P("What caused the Protestant Reformation and what were its main branches?","Think Luther, Calvin, Zwingli, and Henry VIII.","Causes: Church corruption (selling indulgences, absentee clergy); printing press spread criticism; rising nationalism resented papal authority; Renaissance humanism encouraged reading Bible directly. Luther (1517): 95 Theses — salvation by faith alone, scripture as sole authority, priesthood of all believers. Calvin: predestination, theocracy in Geneva. Zwingli: reform in Zurich. English Reformation: Henry VIII broke with Rome for political/dynastic reasons — created Church of England. Result: permanent fragmentation of Western Christianity.","hard"),
      P("How did the Counter-Reformation attempt to respond to Protestantism?","Think Council of Trent and Jesuits.","Counter-Reformation (Catholic Reformation): Council of Trent (1545–63) — clarified Catholic doctrine (rejected sola scriptura, sola fide), reformed clerical abuses, reaffirmed seven sacraments, established seminaries. Society of Jesus (Jesuits, Ignatius Loyola): highly educated missionaries to convert Protestants and expand into Asia and Americas. Inquisition: suppressed heresy in Catholic lands. Index of Forbidden Books. Result: saved much of Europe for Catholicism; defined clear Catholic-Protestant boundary.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Absolutism and Constitutionalism",[
      P("How did Louis XIV exemplify absolute monarchy?","Think divine right, Versailles, and mercantilism.","Louis XIV ('Sun King,' r. 1643–1715): embodied divine right — ruler directly accountable only to God. Power consolidation: weakened nobility by requiring residence at Versailles (spectacle > military power); revoked Edict of Nantes (persecuted Huguenots); controlled Estates-General (never summoned it). Mercantilism: Colbert built French industry, navy, colonies to maximize exports. Wars: War of Spanish Succession expanded French influence but exhausted treasury. Model for absolutism — but left France fiscally fragile.","medium"),
      P("How did England develop constitutional monarchy?","Think Civil War, Glorious Revolution, Bill of Rights.","English Civil War (1642–49): Parliament vs. Charles I over taxation without consent → Charles executed; Cromwell's republic. Restoration (1660): Charles II returned but Parliament retained power. Glorious Revolution (1688): James II fled; William and Mary invited by Parliament. Bill of Rights (1689): Parliament controls taxation, no standing army without consent, freedom of speech in Parliament. Significance: established parliamentary sovereignty, limited monarchy, and rule of law — influenced American and French constitutions.","hard"),
      P("What was the Scientific Revolution and how did it change European thought?","Think methodology and key figures.","Scientific Revolution (1543–1687): Copernicus (heliocentric model); Galileo (telescope, experimental method, conflict with Church); Kepler (elliptical orbits); Newton (laws of motion, gravity). Key shift: from Aristotelian deduction and Church authority to empirical observation and mathematical laws. Method: hypothesis → experiment → conclusion. Implications: human reason can discover natural laws without divine revelation; undermined traditional authority; laid foundation for Enlightenment.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("The French Revolution and Napoleon",[
      P("What caused the French Revolution?","Think financial crisis, social inequality, Enlightenment.","Causes: fiscal crisis (expensive wars, especially American Revolution support); rigid Estates system (clergy and nobility exempt from taxes; Third Estate — 97% of population — bore tax burden); Enlightenment ideas of equality and popular sovereignty; bad harvests (1788) causing bread prices to spike; weak king (Louis XVI) who couldn't reform. Trigger: Louis convened Estates-General (1789) → Third Estate formed National Assembly → Tennis Court Oath → Bastille stormed.","hard"),
      P("What were the key phases of the French Revolution?","Think moderate, radical, Directory.","Phases: (1) Moderate (1789–92): Declaration of Rights of Man, limited monarchy, constitutional reforms. (2) Radical/Reign of Terror (1793–94): Jacobins under Robespierre; Committee of Public Safety; 40,000 executed; levée en masse (citizen army). (3) Thermidorian Reaction (1794): Robespierre guillotined; moderates take control. (4) Directory (1795–99): corrupt, unstable. Napoleon's coup (1799): 18 Brumaire ended Revolution. The Revolution showed Enlightenment ideals could generate both democracy and terror.","hard"),
      P("What was Napoleon's legacy for Europe?","Think reform, nationalism, and reaction.","Napoleon's legacy: spread Napoleonic Code (rational legal system, equal before law, property rights, religious toleration) across Europe; abolished feudalism in conquered territories; demonstrated that ordinary men could rise through merit. But also: military dictatorship; censorship; millions killed in Napoleonic Wars. Stimulated nationalism: French occupation of Germany, Spain, Italy aroused national resistance — nationalism as double-edged legacy. Congress of Vienna (1815): attempted to restore conservative order but couldn't undo nationalism.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("19th Century Revolutions and Reform",[
      P("What was the Congress of Vienna and what were its principles?","Think Metternich and conservative order.","Congress of Vienna (1814–15): European powers met after Napoleon's defeat. Principles: legitimacy (restore pre-revolutionary monarchies), balance of power (prevent dominance by any one state), compensation (territorial adjustments), conservatism (suppress liberalism and nationalism). Metternich (Austria): architect; saw liberalism and nationalism as threats to multinational empires. Created Concert of Europe (great power cooperation). Largely successful: no major European war until 1914, but suppressed reform movements throughout 19th century.","medium"),
      P("What were the 1848 Revolutions and why did they fail?","Think liberal and nationalist uprisings across Europe.","1848 — 'Springtime of Nations': revolutions across France, German states, Austria-Hungary, Italy. Causes: economic hardship, demand for constitutional government, nationalism. Achievements: France briefly republic; Frankfurt Parliament drafted German constitution. Failures: middle class and liberals feared working-class radicalism — chose order over reform; armies remained loyal to old regimes; nationalists disagreed (German vs. Czech vs. Hungarian in Austria); lack of coordination. Result: conservatives restored in most places; but reforms eventually came through different means (Bismarck, Napoleon III).","hard"),
      P("How did industrialization create social problems and reform movements in Britain?","Think urbanization, labor conditions, and reform.","Problems: rapid urbanization without infrastructure (cholera epidemics, overcrowding); child labor in mines and factories; 14-hour workdays; no worker protections. Reform movements: Chartism (working-class political demands); Factory Acts regulated child/female labor; Public Health Act (1848); Reform Acts expanded voting rights (1832, 1867, 1884). Key figures: Edwin Chadwick (sanitation reform), Florence Nightingale (nursing/public health), Shaftesbury (factory reform). Britain reformed gradually — avoided revolution partly through incremental democratic expansion.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("20th Century Europe",[
      P("What were the causes and main phases of the Russian Revolution?","Think 1905, February 1917, October 1917.","Causes: autocratic tsarism unresponsive to reform; massive poverty and inequality; WWI humiliation. 1905 Revolution: Bloody Sunday; Tsar granted Duma (parliament) — then undermined it. February 1917: strikes and mutinies forced Nicholas II to abdicate; Provisional Government (Kerensky) continued unpopular war. October 1917: Bolsheviks (Lenin) seized power — promised 'Peace, Land, Bread.' Civil War (1918–21): Red Army won. Lenin's NEP (compromise with capitalism); Stalin's consolidation — collectivization, purges, industrialization by force.","hard"),
      P("How did the Great Depression contribute to the rise of fascism?","Think economic collapse and political radicalization.","Great Depression (1929+): mass unemployment destroyed faith in liberal democracy and capitalism. Germany: Weimar Republic blamed for WWI humiliation (stab-in-the-back myth) + hyperinflation + Depression → Hitler's NSDAP rose from 2% (1928) to 37% (1932). Nazi appeal: scapegoated Jews and communists; promised national restoration; used propaganda masterfully; offered employment through rearmament. Italy: Mussolini's fascism earlier (1922) exploited WWI grievances. Pattern: democracies vulnerable when they fail to deliver economic security.","hard"),
      P("What was the Holocaust and how did it happen?","Think ideology, bureaucracy, and complicity.","Holocaust: systematic murder of 6 million Jews + 5–6 million others (Roma, disabled, Soviet POWs, homosexuals, Jehovah's Witnesses). Process: Nazi racial ideology (antisemitism + Social Darwinism); Nuremberg Laws (1935) stripped Jewish citizenship; Kristallnacht (1938); invasion of USSR (1941) — Einsatzgruppen mass shootings; Wannsee Conference (1942) coordinated 'Final Solution'; death camps (Auschwitz, Treblinka). Enabled by: bureaucratic organization, ordinary perpetrators, European antisemitism, bystander complicity, Allied failure to prioritize rescue.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Post-WWII Europe",[
      P("How did the Cold War divide Europe?","Think Iron Curtain, NATO, Warsaw Pact.","Cold War in Europe: Soviet sphere — Eastern Europe dominated by communist governments; 'Iron Curtain' (Churchill, 1946). Marshall Plan (1948): US funded Western European recovery — prevented communism through prosperity. Berlin divided: airlift (1948–49); Wall (1961–1989). NATO (1949): Western military alliance. Warsaw Pact (1955): Soviet military alliance. Truman Doctrine: US would support free peoples resisting communist pressure. Germany divided into FRG (West, democratic) and GDR (East, communist) until reunification (1990).","medium"),
      P("What caused the collapse of the Soviet Union?","Think economic stagnation, Gorbachev's reforms, nationalism.","Causes: economic stagnation by 1980s — inefficient central planning, military burden, falling oil prices; Gorbachev's reforms: glasnost (openness — freed political speech) and perestroika (restructuring economy — partial market mechanisms); nationalist movements in Soviet republics (Baltic states, Ukraine, Georgia); 1989 revolutions in Eastern Europe — Soviet Union didn't intervene (unlike 1956, 1968); August 1991 coup attempt failed; republics declared independence; USSR formally dissolved December 1991. Key lesson: political liberalization + economic dysfunction = uncontrollable disintegration.","hard"),
      P("What is the European Union and what problems has it faced?","Think integration and its limits.","EU development: began as European Coal and Steel Community (1951) → EEC (1957) → EU (1993). Achievements: single market, free movement, common currency (Euro, 1999), enlarged to 27 members, prevented intra-European war. Problems: democratic deficit (distant bureaucracy in Brussels); Euro crisis (2010+) — Greece, Spain fiscal crises; migration crisis (2015) — Syrian refugees strained solidarity; Brexit (UK voted to leave 2016, left 2020) — sovereignty concerns; rise of right-wing nationalism challenging EU values. Represents both achievement and ongoing tension between integration and sovereignty.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Cultural and Intellectual History",[
      P("What was the Enlightenment and what were its key ideas?","Think reason, rights, progress.","Enlightenment (18th century): application of reason to human society, politics, and religion. Key ideas: Locke — natural rights (life, liberty, property), government by consent; Rousseau — popular sovereignty, general will; Voltaire — religious toleration, free speech, anti-clericalism; Montesquieu — separation of powers, checks and balances; Adam Smith — free market economics. Legacy: American and French Revolutions; liberal democracy; secular government; human rights discourse.","medium"),
      P("How did Romanticism react against the Enlightenment?","Think emotion, nature, and nationalism.","Romanticism (late 18th–mid 19th century): reaction against Enlightenment rationalism and Industrial Revolution's dehumanization. Emphasized: emotion over reason; nature over civilization; individual genius over social conformity; national culture and history over universal rationalism. Key figures: Goethe, Byron, Shelley, Wordsworth; painters (Delacroix, Friedrich); Beethoven. Political implications: Romantic nationalism — inspired by shared language, culture, folklore → drives Italian and German unification, Polish and Hungarian national movements.","medium"),
      P("How did social darwinism and eugenics influence European thought and policy?","Think misapplication of Darwin and its consequences.","Social Darwinism: Herbert Spencer applied 'survival of the fittest' to human society — justified laissez-faire capitalism, imperialism (stronger nations dominating weaker as 'natural'). Eugenics: Francis Galton proposed improving human 'stock' through selective breeding — restricting reproduction by 'unfit.' Spread: eugenics programs in UK, US, Scandinavia, Germany. Nazi use: racial hygiene laws, forced sterilization, ultimately Holocaust. Demonstrates how scientific-sounding ideology can validate atrocity — eugenics was rejected by genetics; Social Darwinism misunderstood natural selection.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Economic Transformations",[
      P("How did mercantilism differ from liberalism as economic philosophies?","Think state control vs. free market.","Mercantilism (16th–18th century): wealth = gold; state controls economy to maximize exports and minimize imports; colonies provide raw materials and markets; trade is zero-sum (one country's gain = another's loss). Economic liberalism (Adam Smith, Wealth of Nations, 1776): free market; self-interest and price mechanism allocate resources efficiently ('invisible hand'); specialization and trade benefit all; government should not interfere. Liberal economics justified free trade (British industrialists opposed mercantilist tariffs) and undermined colonial trade monopolies.","medium"),
      P("What was the impact of WWI on European economies and societies?","Think mobilization, casualties, and social change.","WWI economic/social impact: total war mobilized entire economies; women entered workforce in large numbers (shifted gender roles); rationing and state control of industry normalized government economic intervention; massive debt to US. Human cost: 10 million military dead, millions more civilians; 'Lost Generation'; Spanish flu (1918) killed 20–50 million worldwide. Social: class system weakened; aristocracy's military prestige destroyed; working-class political power grew; empires collapsed (Ottoman, Austro-Hungarian, Russian, German). Never returned to pre-war liberal optimism.","hard"),
      P("How did European welfare states develop in the 20th century?","Think social democracy and its foundations.","Welfare state development: Great Depression demonstrated market failures; WWII showed state capacity for mobilization; working-class political power (Labour Party in UK, Social Democrats in Scandinavia); Beveridge Report (UK, 1942) — proposed cradle-to-grave social insurance. Post-war: NHS (UK, 1948), universal education, unemployment insurance, housing, pensions. Funded by: high progressive taxation, managed capitalism. 'Golden Age' (1950s–70s): unprecedented prosperity, low inequality. 1980s: Thatcher/Reagan challenged welfare state as economically inefficient.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("War, Diplomacy, and Conflict",[
      P("What were the main causes of WWI?","Think long-term vs. immediate causes.","Long-term: alliance system (Triple Alliance vs. Triple Entente); imperial rivalries; arms race (especially Anglo-German naval race); nationalist tensions (Balkans — 'powder keg of Europe'); Social Darwinist belief in war's inevitability and benefit. Immediate: assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand (June 28, 1914) by Serbian nationalist Gavrilo Princip in Sarajevo → Austria-Hungary ultimatum to Serbia → Russia mobilized to defend Serbia → Germany declared war on Russia and France → Britain entered when Germany violated Belgian neutrality.","medium"),
      P("How did WWII begin and why couldn't appeasement prevent it?","Think Hitler's demands and the limits of appeasement.","Hitler's expansionism: remilitarized Rhineland (1936), Austria Anschluss (1938), Czechoslovakia (Munich Agreement, 1938 — Chamberlain's 'peace in our time'). Appeasement rationale: WWI horror made leaders desperate to avoid war; believed Hitler had legitimate grievances; hoped economic concessions would stabilize Germany. Why it failed: Hitler interpreted appeasement as weakness; demands escalated with each concession; Poland invasion (September 1939) → Britain and France finally declared war. Lesson: appeasement of aggressor emboldens rather than satisfies.","hard"),
      P("How did European integration develop as a response to WWII?","Think Schuman Plan and incremental integration.","European integration logic: Franco-German reconciliation essential; economic interdependence would prevent future war; shared institutions would create common identity. Steps: European Coal and Steel Community (1951) — pooled coal/steel to make war materially impossible; Rome Treaty (1957) — European Economic Community (Common Market); Single European Act (1986) — completed internal market; Maastricht Treaty (1993) — created EU, planned Euro; Euro (1999). Jean Monnet's 'functionalist' theory: economic integration would gradually produce political integration — largely confirmed, though not complete.","hard"),
    ]),
  ],
  # Unit 4 — AP US Government and Politics
  [
    T("Constitutional Foundations",[
      P("What are the key principles of the US Constitution?","Think separation of powers, federalism, checks and balances.","Key principles: (1) Separation of powers: legislative (Congress), executive (President), judicial (Supreme Court) each have distinct functions; (2) Checks and balances: each branch can limit the others (veto, Senate confirmation, judicial review); (3) Federalism: power divided between federal and state governments; (4) Popular sovereignty: government derives power from the people; (5) Limited government: government power constrained by Constitution and Bill of Rights; (6) Judicial review (Marbury v. Madison): courts can strike down unconstitutional laws.","medium"),
      P("How does the amendment process work and what does it reveal about the Constitution?","Think Article V and difficulty of amendment.","Amendment process: Congress proposes (2/3 majority of both chambers) OR constitutional convention called by 2/3 of states → ratified by 3/4 of states (38 of 50). Deliberately difficult — founders wanted stability. Only 27 amendments in 230+ years; first 10 (Bill of Rights) ratified together (1791). Reveals: founders distrusted majoritarian rule; wanted supermajority consensus for fundamental change; created flexibility through deliberate difficulty. Consequence: much constitutional change happens through judicial reinterpretation rather than formal amendment.","medium"),
      P("What is federalism and how has the balance of power between federal and state governments shifted?","Think dual vs. cooperative federalism.","Federalism: constitutional division of power between national and state governments. Dual federalism ('layer cake,' pre-New Deal): clear separation — federal government has enumerated powers; states have reserved powers (10th Amendment). Cooperative federalism ('marble cake,' New Deal+): federal-state partnership through grants-in-aid, shared programs (Medicaid, highway system). New federalism (Nixon, Reagan): return power to states through block grants. McCulloch v. Maryland (1819): established federal supremacy + implied powers (necessary and proper clause). Current reality: federal power vastly expanded through commerce clause, spending power.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Branches of Government",[
      P("What are the formal and informal powers of the President?","Think constitutional vs. extra-constitutional power.","Formal (constitutional) powers: commander-in-chief of military; nominate Supreme Court justices and cabinet; veto legislation; make treaties (with Senate ratification); pardon power; deliver State of the Union. Informal/extra-constitutional powers: executive orders (legally binding presidential directives); executive privilege (withhold information from Congress/courts); agenda-setting through State of the Union and media; use of bully pulpit to pressure Congress and public opinion. Presidents have consistently expanded power — especially in national security — often at expense of Congress.","medium"),
      P("How does Congress perform its oversight function?","Think checks on executive power.","Congressional oversight: Constitution's 'implied' power to monitor executive branch. Methods: committee hearings (summon executive officials, whistleblowers); confirmation hearings (Senate confirms nominees); power of the purse (appropriate or deny funding); investigations (select committees, GAO audits); War Powers Resolution (1973) — limits presidential military action without Congressional authorization. Limits: partisanship undermines oversight when same party controls Congress and White House; information asymmetry (executive knows more than Congress); filibuster can block legislative responses to executive overreach.","hard"),
      P("What is judicial review and how has the Supreme Court used it?","Think landmark cases.","Judicial review: Marbury v. Madison (1803) established that Supreme Court can strike down laws violating Constitution. Key cases: McCulloch v. Maryland (1819) — federal power broad; Brown v. Board (1954) — desegregated schools; Roe v. Wade (1973) — abortion right (overturned Dobbs 2022); Bush v. Gore (2000) — decided presidential election; Obergefell v. Hodges (2015) — same-sex marriage. Debate: judicial activism (use courts to advance rights) vs. judicial restraint (defer to elected branches). Court's power depends on compliance — has no enforcement mechanism (relies on elected branches to implement decisions).","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Civil Liberties and Civil Rights",[
      P("What is the difference between civil liberties and civil rights?","Think negative vs. positive rights.","Civil liberties: protections from government action — what government CANNOT do (restrict free speech, search without warrant, deny due process). Grounded in Bill of Rights. Civil rights: positive guarantees of equal treatment — what government MUST do (ensure equal access regardless of race, gender, etc.). Grounded in 14th Amendment's Equal Protection Clause. Examples: 1st Amendment (liberty — government cannot restrict speech); Civil Rights Act 1964 (rights — government must prevent discrimination). Selective incorporation: Supreme Court has applied most Bill of Rights provisions to states via 14th Amendment.","medium"),
      P("How has the Supreme Court interpreted the 1st Amendment?","Think categories of protected and unprotected speech.","1st Amendment: 'Congress shall make no law...abridging the freedom of speech.' Interpretations: Protected: political speech, symbolic speech (flag burning — Texas v. Johnson), commercial speech (limited), offensive speech. Unprotected: incitement to imminent lawless action (Brandenburg v. Ohio), 'true threats,' obscenity (Miller test), defamation (false statements of fact). Prior restraint: heavily disfavored (Pentagon Papers case). Campaign finance: Citizens United (2010) — political spending = protected speech, cannot be limited. Tension: free expression vs. protection from harm.","hard"),
      P("How has the Equal Protection Clause been used to expand civil rights?","Think levels of scrutiny.","14th Amendment Equal Protection: government cannot deny equal protection of laws. Courts apply different scrutiny levels: (1) Rational basis (most laws): just needs plausible reason; (2) Intermediate scrutiny (gender): substantially related to important government interest; (3) Strict scrutiny (race, national origin, fundamental rights): must serve compelling interest through narrowly tailored means. Key cases: Brown v. Board (race/education); Reed v. Reed (gender); Obergefell (sexual orientation, applied rational basis+). Affirmative action: Bakke (1978), Grutter (2003), struck down in Students for Fair Admissions (2023).","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Political Participation",[
      P("How does the Electoral College work and what debates surround it?","Think selection mechanism and criticisms.","Electoral College: each state gets electors = senators + representatives (DC gets 3 via 23rd Amendment). 538 total; 270 needed to win. Most states: winner-take-all by state popular vote. Criticisms: (1) Presidents can win without popular vote (2000, 2016); (2) Battleground states dominate campaigns; (3) Small states overrepresented. Defenses: (1) Protects smaller states; (2) Encourages broad geographic coalition; (3) Usually amplifies winner's margin (clear legitimacy). Changing requires constitutional amendment — difficult due to small-state advantage in Senate.","medium"),
      P("What factors explain low voter turnout in the United States?","Think structural and behavioral explanations.","Structural: registration requirements (most countries auto-register citizens); Tuesday voting (workday); few polling places in some areas; felony disenfranchisement; voter ID laws (disputed). Behavioral: political efficacy (do I make a difference?); civic education; candidate quality; mobilization efforts. Comparisons: US turnout (~55–65% in presidential elections) lower than most democracies. Higher turnout groups: older, higher-income, more educated. Lower: young, lower-income, minority (in some jurisdictions). Voting Rights Act (1965) dramatically increased Black turnout; subsequent restrictions have faced legal challenges.","medium"),
      P("What is the role of interest groups in American democracy?","Think pluralism and its critics.","Interest groups: organizations that advocate for specific policy goals. Methods: lobbying (direct contact with legislators), campaign contributions (PACs, Super PACs), grassroots mobilization, litigation, media campaigns. Pluralist defense: competing interest groups reflect diverse citizen preferences; prevents tyranny. Critiques: wealthy interests better organized and funded (elite theory); revolving door (lobbying by former officials); 'iron triangles' (congressional committees, executive agencies, interest groups work together, excluding public). Citizens United (2010): unlimited independent spending. Campaign finance remains major democracy debate.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Public Policy",[
      P("What is the policymaking process in the US?","Think stages and actors.","Policy process: (1) Agenda setting: issue recognized as requiring government action (media, crises, advocacy); (2) Policy formulation: proposals developed (think tanks, Congress, executive agencies); (3) Adoption: legislative process (committee, floor vote, conference, presidential signature); (4) Implementation: executive agencies carry out law (bureaucratic discretion); (5) Evaluation: courts, Congress, GAO assess outcomes. Multiple veto points: federalism, bicameralism, presidential veto, Senate filibuster, judicial review — make policy change difficult (gridlock) but also protect against hasty change.","medium"),
      P("How does the budget process work and what drives the national debt?","Think discretionary vs. mandatory spending.","Budget: President proposes; Congress passes appropriations (discretionary spending — defense, education, etc.) and authorizes entitlement programs (mandatory — Social Security, Medicare, Medicaid). Mandatory spending: ~65% of federal budget; grows automatically with demographics. Discretionary: subject to annual appropriation — can be cut. Revenue: income tax, payroll tax, corporate tax. Debt: accumulated deficits. Political dynamic: everyone wants services, few want taxes; entitlements politically difficult to cut (large voting blocs); military spending politically popular. CBO provides nonpartisan analysis.","hard"),
      P("What is federalism's role in social policy?","Think variation across states.","Federalism creates laboratory of democracy: states can experiment with policies; successful ones can spread nationally (Massachusetts healthcare → ACA model). Also creates inequality: safety net programs vary dramatically by state (Medicaid expansion — some states opted out); voting rights; criminal justice; education funding tied to local property taxes. Federal grants: coercive (attached conditions) or flexible (block grants). Current debates: which level should handle healthcare, climate, immigration, marijuana? Supreme Court increasingly limits federal power (NFIB v. Sebelius, West Virginia v. EPA) — returning power to states.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Political Culture and Parties",[
      P("What is political culture and what values define American political culture?","Think core beliefs.","American political culture: widely shared beliefs about government and politics. Core values: individualism (personal responsibility, limited government); liberty (freedom from government interference); equality of opportunity (not outcome); democracy (popular sovereignty); rule of law. Tocqueville observed: Americans unusually civic-minded despite individualism; voluntary associations mediate between individual and state. These values are contested in practice (liberty vs. equality; individual vs. collective) but shape the range of acceptable policy debate — explains why US has no major socialist party unlike European democracies.","medium"),
      P("How have American political parties changed since the 1960s?","Think sorting and polarization.","Pre-1960s: ideologically mixed — liberal Republicans (Rockefeller), conservative Democrats (Southern Dixiecrats). Civil Rights era: realignment — white Southern Democrats moved to Republican Party; Black voters solidified Democratic. Since 1980s: ideological sorting — parties became more internally uniform. Since 1990s: polarization — moderate members declined; partisanship intensified; negative partisanship (voting against opponent rather than for candidate). Causes: geographic sorting (like-minded communities), media fragmentation, primary elections (activate base voters), campaign finance. Result: increasing legislative gridlock.","hard"),
      P("What role does the media play in American democracy?","Think agenda-setting and fragmentation.","Media functions: watchdog (investigative journalism holds power accountable); agenda-setting (what media covers → what public and politicians consider important); framing (how stories are presented shapes interpretation). Challenges: fragmentation — cable news, social media create partisan echo chambers; declining local news deserts; social media algorithms reward outrage and engagement over accuracy; 'horse race' journalism covers strategy over policy; foreign influence operations exploit open information environment. FCC once required balanced coverage (Fairness Doctrine, repealed 1987); no equivalent exists for cable or internet.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Comparative Government Connections",[
      P("How does the US system compare to parliamentary systems?","Think separation of powers vs. fusion of powers.","Presidential system (US): separate elections for executive and legislative; president serves fixed term; can have divided government. Parliamentary system (UK, Germany): executive (Prime Minister) chosen by legislature; government falls if loses parliamentary majority; generally more efficient legislating but less stable. Advantages of presidential: clear democratic mandate for president; protects against legislative tyranny. Disadvantages: gridlock when divided government; weak party discipline; lame-duck periods. Most new democracies since 1945 chose parliamentary systems — US model considered unusually difficult to maintain.","hard"),
      P("What is the role of bureaucracy in implementing public policy?","Think discretion and accountability.","Federal bureaucracy: 2+ million civilian employees; Cabinet departments, independent agencies, regulatory commissions, government corporations. Functions: implement legislation (discretion fills gaps Congress leaves), regulate (rulemaking — proposed rules → public comment → final rule), adjudicate disputes. Accountability mechanisms: Senate confirmation of top officials, congressional oversight hearings, inspector generals, GAO audits, FOIA requests, presidential appointment power. Principal-agent problem: bureaucrats may pursue their own preferences rather than elected officials' intent. Reform debates: civil service vs. political appointees; deregulation vs. regulatory state.","medium"),
    ]),
  ],
  # Unit 5 — AP Comparative Government
  [
    T("Comparative Methods and Concepts",[
      P("What is the purpose of comparative politics?","Think why we compare political systems.","Comparative politics: systematic study of political institutions, behavior, and processes across different countries to explain why political outcomes differ. Goals: test hypotheses about causation ('does presidentialism produce instability?'); understand our own system better through contrast; predict political change; evaluate policy effectiveness across contexts. Methods: case study (deep analysis of one country), cross-national comparison (many countries), 'most similar systems' (compare similar countries with different outcomes), 'most different systems' (compare different countries with similar outcomes).","medium"),
      P("What is a state and what makes one legitimate?","Think Weber and political authority.","State: organization with monopoly on legitimate use of force within a defined territory (Weber's definition). Elements: territory, population, government, sovereignty (external recognition). Legitimacy: citizens accept government authority as rightful. Sources of legitimacy: traditional (custom, monarchy by divine right), charismatic (personal authority of leader), rational-legal (rule of law, procedures). Failed states: lose monopoly on force (Somalia, Libya); challenged states: face significant internal armed opposition. Democracy derives legitimacy from popular consent — elections are its primary legitimating mechanism.","medium"),
      P("What is a regime type and how do democracies differ from authoritarian states?","Think spectrum of regimes.","Regime types: liberal democracy (free elections, civil liberties, rule of law, civilian control of military, independent judiciary), electoral authoritarianism (holds elections but manipulates them, restricts opposition), hybrid/competitive authoritarian, full authoritarianism (no meaningful elections), totalitarianism (state controls all aspects of life — Nazi Germany, Soviet Union). Key distinctions: contestation (can opposition parties meaningfully compete?) and participation (can citizens meaningfully engage?). Democratic backsliding: gradual erosion of democratic norms and institutions in formally democratic states.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Case Studies: UK, Russia, China",[
      P("How does the UK's Westminster system function?","Think parliamentary sovereignty and fusion of powers.","Westminster model: Parliament is sovereign — can pass any law. Prime Minister is leader of majority party in House of Commons; controls government through party discipline; can call elections (within limits). House of Lords: unelected upper chamber, can delay but not block legislation. Constitutional conventions (unwritten): constrain power despite no codified constitution. Key features: first-past-the-post electoral system (tends to produce two-party dominance); 'loyal opposition' formalizes minority role; PM's Questions (accountability mechanism). Brexit demonstrated: Parliamentary sovereignty can override EU law — but at enormous political cost.","medium"),
      P("How has Russia developed as a hybrid authoritarian state under Putin?","Think managed democracy and power consolidation.","Russia after 1991: weak democracy under Yeltsin; oligarchs dominated; financial crisis (1998). Putin (2000+): gradually consolidated power. Mechanisms: controlled elections (opposition harassed, banned, or killed); Kremlin-friendly media dominate; federal power centralized (governors appointed); security services (FSB) embedded in government; selective use of courts against opponents (Navalny). Economy: state capitalism — strategic sectors (oil, gas) controlled by loyalists; oligarchs dependent on Kremlin favor. Foreign policy: restore great power status; Ukraine invasions (2014, 2022). Classified as 'electoral authoritarian' — elections held but not meaningfully competitive.","hard"),
      P("How does the Chinese Communist Party maintain its political monopoly?","Think control mechanisms and performance legitimacy.","CCP control mechanisms: monopoly on party membership and ideology; control of media and internet (Great Firewall); surveillance technology (social credit system, facial recognition); party cells in all institutions (universities, businesses, military); co-opt business and intellectual elites; suppress dissent (Tiananmen 1989, Xinjiang, Hong Kong National Security Law). Legitimacy: performance legitimacy (economic growth — 800 million lifted from poverty since 1980) replaces electoral legitimacy; nationalism; historical CCP narrative. Xi Jinping (2012+): concentrated power further, abolished presidential term limits, launched anti-corruption campaign (also eliminates rivals).","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Political Economy",[
      P("What is the difference between command economies and market economies?","Think allocation mechanisms.","Command/planned economy: state owns means of production; government allocates resources through planning; prices set administratively. Soviet model: rapid industrialization in 1930s; inefficient allocation; shortages; black markets. Market economy: prices allocate resources through supply and demand; private ownership; competition; innovation incentive. Mixed economy: most real economies — private markets with government regulation, safety nets, and intervention in market failures. China's model: 'socialist market economy' — private enterprise + CCP political control + state ownership of strategic sectors.","medium"),
      P("How does oil wealth affect governance in petrostates?","Think resource curse.","Resource curse: oil/mineral wealth often correlates with authoritarianism and poor governance. Mechanisms: (1) Rentier state — government revenues from oil, not taxes → less accountable to citizens ('no taxation without representation' in reverse); (2) Incumbents use oil revenues to buy loyalty (patronage) and repress opposition; (3) Dutch disease — oil exports raise currency, making other exports uncompetitive; (4) Volatility — economy hostage to commodity price swings. Examples: Nigeria (oil wealth, poverty, corruption), Saudi Arabia (rentier state), Russia (dependent on energy exports). Norway: exception — democratic institutions + sovereign wealth fund managed oil wealth well.","hard"),
      P("How do different welfare state models affect economic outcomes?","Think liberal, conservative, social democratic models.","Esping-Andersen's three worlds: (1) Liberal welfare state (US, UK): means-tested benefits, private insurance emphasized, inequality higher; (2) Conservative/corporatist (Germany, France): social insurance tied to employment, church/family role; (3) Social democratic (Nordic): universal benefits, high taxes, low inequality, high gender equality. Outcomes: Nordic countries combine high equality WITH high economic competitiveness — challenge to 'equality-efficiency tradeoff' argument. Liberal welfare states: more dynamic labor markets but more poverty and insecurity. Debate: can Nordic model be transplanted to different cultural/economic contexts?","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Political Change",[
      P("What causes democratic transitions?","Think structural and agency-based explanations.","Structural factors: modernization theory (wealth, education, middle class correlate with democracy); previous democratic experience; regional diffusion (democracy in neighbors); civil society strength. Agency: elite choices during transitions — whether military accepts civilian control; whether oppositions negotiate or fight. Waves: first wave (19th century), second (post-WWII), third (1974+ — Southern Europe, Latin America, Eastern Europe, some Africa/Asia). Backsliding wave: Hungary, Poland, Turkey, Venezuela, others — democracies eroding without military coup. Key: democracy requires both institutions AND democratic culture/norms.","hard"),
      P("What is civil society and why is it important for democracy?","Think intermediary organizations.","Civil society: voluntary associations between family and state — NGOs, religious institutions, labor unions, professional associations, civic groups. Functions: (1) Aggregates and represents citizen interests; (2) Monitors government (watchdog); (3) Builds civic skills and trust (social capital); (4) Provides services; (5) Limits state power. Tocqueville: American democracy depended on associational life. Authoritarian states suppress civil society (Russia's 'foreign agent' laws target NGOs). Weakness of civil society: associated with democratic fragility in post-communist states that lacked organized opposition during communist era.","medium"),
      P("How do electoral systems affect political outcomes?","Think proportional vs. majoritarian.","Majoritarian systems (FPTP — UK, US): candidates/parties win districts; encourages two-party systems (Duverger's Law); stable governments; but many votes 'wasted'; third parties disadvantaged. Proportional representation (most of Europe): parties receive seats proportional to votes; more parties represented; coalition governments; minor parties viable. Mixed systems (Germany, Japan): combine both. Consequences: PR tends toward more parties, coalition governments, higher representation of women and minorities, more policy proportional to voter preferences; FPTP tends toward clearer accountability and single-party governments.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Identity and Politics",[
      P("How does ethnic diversity affect political stability?","Think power-sharing mechanisms.","Ethnic diversity and conflict: not automatic — many diverse societies are stable; many homogeneous ones have civil wars. Risk factors: ethnic entrepreneurs who mobilize ethnic identity for political gain; 'winner take all' electoral systems (majority group can permanently exclude minorities); legacies of colonialism (arbitrary borders). Power-sharing mechanisms: consociationalism (formal power-sharing across ethnic groups — Lebanon, Bosnia); federalism (territorial autonomy for minorities); proportional representation (minorities get legislative voice); veto rights for minority groups. Case: Switzerland — four languages, stable democracy through federalism and proportionality.","hard"),
      P("How do postcolonial legacies affect governance in the developing world?","Think institutional and economic inheritance.","Colonial legacies: (1) Borders drawn without regard for ethnic/linguistic communities → civil conflicts; (2) Extractive institutions (exploit colony) not developmental → weak state capacity inherited; (3) Economic specialization in raw material exports → commodity dependence; (4) Language of colonial power as official language → communication but cultural alienation; (5) Different colonial strategies: British indirect rule (preserved local elites) vs. French assimilation (replaced local institutions). Long-term effects measurable: Acemoglu, Johnson, Robinson show colonizer identity and strategy predict current institutional quality.","hard"),
    ]),
  ],
  # Unit 6 — AP Human Geography
  [
    T("Thinking Geographically",[
      P("What is the difference between absolute and relative location?","Think coordinates vs. context.","Absolute location: exact position on Earth's surface using coordinate system (latitude/longitude) or street address. Unique and unchanging. Relative location: position relative to other places and features — 'north of Chicago,' 'near the river,' 'in the downtown.' Changes as surroundings change. Both matter: GPS uses absolute; real estate agents use relative (location relative to schools, transit, jobs). Human geography focuses more on relative location — how places relate to each other economically, culturally, and politically.","easy"),
      P("What is the difference between space and place?","Think abstract vs. meaningful.","Space: abstract, geometric — an area defined by coordinates or distance. Place: space that has been given meaning through human experience, culture, and identity — 'my hometown,' 'Ground Zero,' 'the Holy Land.' Topophilia: strong sense of place attachment. Placelessness (Relph): landscapes become identical (strip malls, chain restaurants) — loss of distinctive place identity. Humanistic geography focuses on place meaning and experience. Space becomes place when people invest it with meaning through lived experience, memory, and cultural practice.","medium"),
      P("What are the major map projections and what distortions do they introduce?","Think Mercator, Peters, and Robinson.","Map projections: all 2D maps of 3D Earth introduce distortion in area, shape, distance, or direction. Mercator: preserves direction (useful for navigation), distorts area (Greenland appears larger than Africa — false). Peters/Gall-Peters: preserves area, distorts shape (used to challenge Eurocentric size bias). Robinson: compromise — distorts both but minimizes extreme distortions. AzimuthalEquidistant: preserves distance from center point. Political implications: map choice shapes perception of relative country sizes and importance.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Population and Migration",[
      P("What is the demographic transition model?","Think stages of population growth.","DTM: model describing how countries' birth and death rates change with development. Stage 1: high birth rates, high death rates — slow growth (pre-industrial). Stage 2: death rates fall (medicine, sanitation), birth rates stay high — rapid population growth (early industrial). Stage 3: birth rates fall as urbanization increases — growth slows. Stage 4: low birth, low death — stable or slow growth (post-industrial). Stage 5 (proposed): birth rates below replacement — population decline (Germany, Japan). Most LDCs in stages 2–3; MDCs in stages 4–5.","medium"),
      P("What are the push and pull factors in migration?","Think why people leave and why they go where they do.","Push factors: reasons to leave origin — poverty, lack of jobs, war/conflict, political persecution, environmental degradation, drought/famine, discrimination. Pull factors: reasons to choose destination — economic opportunity, political freedom, family already there (chain migration), better environment, education. Ravenstein's Laws: most migrants move short distances; migration flows in steps; urban areas attract more migrants. Forced vs. voluntary: refugees and asylum seekers are forced (cannot safely return) vs. economic migrants (voluntary). Remittances: migrants send money home — major source of income for some countries (Philippines, Mexico, El Salvador).","medium"),
      P("What is the epidemiological transition and how does it relate to economic development?","Think causes of death changing with development.","Epidemiological transition: as countries develop, cause of death shifts from infectious/communicable diseases to chronic/degenerative diseases. Stage 1: pestilence and famine dominate (cholera, plague, starvation). Stage 2: receding pandemics as sanitation and medicine improve. Stage 3: degenerative and man-made diseases (heart disease, cancer, accidents) as people live longer. Stage 4: delayed degenerative diseases (diseases pushed to older ages through better treatment). Linked to DTM: falling death rates in Stage 2 reflect epidemiological transition. Contemporary: LDCs face 'double burden' — still fighting infectious disease while chronic diseases increase.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Cultural Patterns",[
      P("What is the difference between folk culture and popular culture?","Think local vs. global.","Folk culture: traditional, locally developed practices — transmitted through oral tradition and observation; tends to be place-specific; reflects local environment and history; changes slowly; examples: Appalachian quilting, regional foodways. Popular culture: widely distributed via mass media and communication; produced commercially; relatively uniform across space; changes rapidly; examples: Hollywood films, global fashion, fast food. Globalization spreading popular culture raises concern about cultural homogenization ('McDonaldization') — loss of folk cultural diversity. But cultures also hybridize rather than simply replacing one another.","medium"),
      P("How does religion shape human geography?","Think sacred space, cultural landscape, and conflict.","Religion shapes: (1) Cultural landscape — mosques, churches, temples, burial practices, pilgrimage routes; (2) Sacred space — Jerusalem, Mecca, Varanasi — centers of pilgrimage and conflict; (3) Calendars and time — Sabbath, Ramadan, Hindu festivals; (4) Dietary practices — halal, kosher, vegetarianism shape food geography; (5) Conflict — religious boundaries often coincide with political conflict zones (Northern Ireland, Balkans, Kashmir, Middle East); (6) Universalizing vs. ethnic religions — universalizing (Christianity, Islam, Buddhism) actively seek converts and spread globally; ethnic (Hinduism, Judaism) tied to specific communities.","medium"),
      P("What is cultural diffusion and what are its types?","Think how culture spreads.","Cultural diffusion: spread of cultural elements from origin (hearth) to other areas. Types: (1) Relocation diffusion — immigrants carry culture to new location; (2) Expansion diffusion: a. Contagious — spreads from person to person in waves (disease, internet memes); b. Hierarchical — spreads from large cities to smaller (fashion, music trends); c. Stimulus — idea spreads but adapts to local conditions (McDonald's adapts menu globally). Barriers to diffusion: physical (mountains, oceans), cultural (religious prohibition), political. Time-space compression: modern communication technology dramatically speeds diffusion.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Political Geography",[
      P("What is the difference between a nation, a state, and a nation-state?","Think political geography's key terms.","State: politically organized territory with sovereignty, defined borders, permanent population, and recognized government. Nation: group of people with shared identity — culture, language, history, ethnicity. Nation-state: a state whose territory corresponds to a specific nation — the 'ideal' unit of modern politics, but rare in practice (most states are multinational). Stateless nation: nation without its own state (Kurds, Palestinians, Tibetans). Multistate nation: nation spread across multiple states (divided Korea, Germany before unification). Most political conflict involves the gap between national identity and state boundaries.","medium"),
      P("What is gerrymandering and how does it affect political representation?","Think district drawing and its effects.","Gerrymandering: manipulating electoral district boundaries to favor one party or group. Types: 'cracking' (spreading opposing voters across many districts so they never form majority); 'packing' (concentrating opposing voters in one district — they win there but lose everywhere else). Effects: creates 'safe seats' — incumbents almost never lose; reduces competitive elections; allows parties to choose voters rather than voters choosing parties. Racial gerrymandering: prohibited by Voting Rights Act (can't deliberately dilute minority voting power). Partisan gerrymandering: Supreme Court ruled in Rucho v. Common Cause (2019) that federal courts cannot remedy it — leaves to states.","hard"),
      P("How does supranationalism challenge state sovereignty?","Think EU and global governance.","Supranationalism: pooling sovereignty among multiple states to achieve common goals — states voluntarily cede some authority to a higher body. Examples: European Union (member states share monetary policy, trade regulation, border control); NAFTA/USMCA (trade rules); NATO (collective defense commitments); UN (limited but real authority in peacekeeping, international law). Tension: states gain benefits (economic integration, security) but lose autonomy. Brexit: UK chose sovereignty over EU integration. Contemporary debates: climate change, pandemic response, and migration require supranational cooperation, but nationalism resists sovereignty transfer.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Development Geography",[
      P("What is the Human Development Index and what does it measure?","Think beyond GDP.","HDI (UNDP): composite measure of development combining three dimensions: (1) Health — life expectancy at birth; (2) Education — mean years of schooling + expected years; (3) Standard of living — GNI per capita (PPP). Scales 0–1; countries divided into very high, high, medium, low. Advantages over GDP alone: captures quality of life (not just economic output); accounts for distribution somewhat. Limitations: still doesn't capture inequality, sustainability, political freedom, happiness. Supplement with: Gender Inequality Index, Multidimensional Poverty Index. Norway typically ranks #1.","medium"),
      P("What is dependency theory and how does it explain global inequality?","Think core-periphery relationships.","Dependency theory: LDC poverty is not due to internal failures but to structural relationships between core (wealthy) and periphery (poor) countries. Historical: colonialism extracted raw materials from colonies, developed metropoles, underdeveloped colonies. Contemporary: MNCs extract profits from periphery; terms of trade favor manufactured goods (core) over raw materials (periphery); debt trap; brain drain. World-systems theory (Wallerstein): core, semi-periphery, periphery — hierarchical global capitalist system that perpetuates inequality. Contrasts with modernization theory (which attributes poverty to internal cultural/institutional factors).","hard"),
      P("What is sustainable development and why is it difficult to achieve?","Think Brundtland definition and tensions.","Sustainable development (Brundtland Commission, 1987): 'development that meets the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs.' Tensions: (1) Economic growth vs. environmental limits (carbon emissions, deforestation, species loss); (2) Current poor countries need development — but path of industrial countries is environmentally unsustainable; (3) Present consumption vs. future costs; (4) National interest vs. global commons. SDGs (2015): 17 goals including poverty, education, climate, gender equality — attempt to operationalize sustainable development. Key debate: can capitalism be reformed for sustainability, or does it require fundamental system change?","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Urban and Rural Land Use",[
      P("What are the main models of urban structure?","Think Burgess, Hoyt, and Harris-Ullman.","Concentric Zone Model (Burgess): city grows outward in rings from CBD — CBD, transition zone (industry/slums), working-class housing, middle-class, commuter zone. Sector Model (Hoyt): city grows in sectors/wedges along transportation routes — wealthy and poor sectors extend outward. Multiple Nuclei Model (Harris-Ullman): cities develop around multiple centers (CBD, industrial district, university, airport) — more realistic for modern US cities. Most useful for understanding North American cities; European and LDC cities have different patterns (wealthy near center, poor in periphery in many LDCs).","medium"),
      P("What is suburbanization and what has driven it in the United States?","Think push/pull factors and consequences.","Suburbanization: population and economic activity moving from city centers to periphery. US drivers: GI Bill mortgages after WWII; Interstate Highway System; racial 'white flight' from desegregating cities; cheap land; automobile culture; 'good schools' in suburban districts. Consequences: urban fiscal crisis (tax base moved out, costs remained); environmental sprawl and car dependence; segregation by race and class; 'edge cities' emerging as suburban employment centers. Recent counter-trend: gentrification (wealthy moving back to city centers) displacing lower-income residents.","medium"),
    ]),
  ],
  # Unit 7 — AP Macroeconomics
  [
    T("Basic Economic Concepts",[
      P("What is the difference between macroeconomics and microeconomics?","Think scale of analysis.","Microeconomics: individual economic agents — consumers, firms, specific markets. Focuses on: supply and demand for specific goods, price determination, market structure (competition, monopoly), individual firm behavior, consumer choice. Macroeconomics: economy as a whole — national output, employment, price levels, economic growth. Focuses on: GDP, unemployment rate, inflation, monetary and fiscal policy, trade balances. Macro questions: What causes recessions? How should government respond to unemployment? What causes inflation? They're connected — macro emerges from aggregation of micro behavior.","easy"),
      P("What is GDP and what are the four components of aggregate expenditure?","Think measuring total output.","GDP (Gross Domestic Product): total market value of all final goods and services produced within a country in a given time period. Expenditure approach: GDP = C + I + G + (X - M). C: household consumption (largest ~70% of US GDP). I: investment — business fixed investment, residential construction, inventory changes. G: government spending (not transfer payments like Social Security). X-M: net exports (exports minus imports). Other approaches: income approach (sum all factor payments) and production approach — all should yield same result.","medium"),
      P("What is the difference between real and nominal GDP?","Think adjusting for price changes.","Nominal GDP: total output measured at current year's prices — increases both when output increases AND when prices increase. Real GDP: total output measured at base year's prices — controls for price changes, so changes reflect only changes in actual output (quantity). Real GDP used to measure actual economic growth and compare across years. GDP deflator: price index used to convert nominal to real GDP. Formula: Real GDP = (Nominal GDP / GDP Deflator) × 100. Per capita GDP: GDP divided by population — better measure of living standards than total GDP.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Economic Indicators",[
      P("How is unemployment measured and what are its types?","Think BLS methodology and categories.","Unemployment rate: (unemployed / labor force) × 100. Labor force: employed + unemployed (those actively seeking work). Not counted: discouraged workers (stopped looking), part-time workers seeking full-time (underemployment). Types: (1) Frictional — between jobs; temporary; normal in dynamic economy; (2) Structural — skills mismatch due to technological change or economic restructuring; more persistent; (3) Cyclical — demand-deficient; caused by recessions; (4) Seasonal — varies with seasons (agriculture, tourism). Natural rate of unemployment (NRU): frictional + structural — 'full employment' in macro sense; approximately 4–5% in US.","medium"),
      P("What is inflation and how is it measured?","Think CPI and its effects.","Inflation: sustained increase in the general price level. CPI (Consumer Price Index): tracks price of typical consumer 'basket' of goods and services; Bureau of Labor Statistics; used for Social Security adjustments, wage negotiations. Core CPI: excludes volatile food and energy. GDP Deflator: broader measure of price changes in entire economy. PCE Deflator: Fed's preferred inflation measure. Effects of inflation: erodes purchasing power (bad for savers, creditors); benefits debtors; creates uncertainty. Hyperinflation: extremely rapid inflation (Germany 1923, Zimbabwe 2008) destroys economic function. Deflation: falling prices — worse than mild inflation because delays spending (prices will be lower tomorrow) → recession spiral.","hard"),
      P("What is the business cycle and what are its phases?","Think expansion, peak, contraction, trough.","Business cycle: recurring fluctuations in economic activity. Phases: Expansion — rising real GDP, employment, and incomes; Peak — maximum output before decline; Contraction/Recession — falling real GDP for 2+ consecutive quarters; Trough — minimum output before recovery. Leading indicators: predict future activity (stock prices, new orders, building permits). Lagging indicators: confirm cycle (unemployment rate, prime rate). Coincident indicators: move with current economy (employment, personal income). Recessions caused by: demand shocks (financial crises), supply shocks (oil price spikes), policy errors (overly tight monetary policy).","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Aggregate Demand and Supply",[
      P("What is aggregate demand and why does the AD curve slope downward?","Think three effects.","Aggregate demand (AD): total spending on goods and services at different price levels. Downward slope: (1) Wealth effect — higher price level reduces real value of savings → less spending; (2) Interest rate effect — higher prices → more money needed → interest rates rise → investment falls; (3) Net export effect — higher domestic prices make exports less competitive, imports more attractive → net exports fall. AD curve shifts (not price level changes): changes in consumption (wealth, expectations), investment (business confidence, interest rates), government spending, net exports (foreign income, exchange rates).","hard"),
      P("What is aggregate supply and how does it differ in short run vs. long run?","Think SRAS vs. LRAS.","Short-run aggregate supply (SRAS): upward sloping — higher price levels lead firms to produce more in short run (nominal wages and input costs sticky in short run). Shifts: changes in input costs (wages, energy), productivity, business taxes/subsidies, expectations. Long-run aggregate supply (LRAS): vertical line at potential GDP/full employment output — in long run, wages and prices fully flexible; output determined by resource quantities and technology, not price level. Shifts: changes in resource quantities (population, capital stock), technology, institutions. Short-run equilibrium can differ from long-run potential (recessionary or inflationary gap).","hard"),
      P("What are recessionary and inflationary gaps and how are they corrected?","Think self-correction and policy intervention.","Recessionary gap: short-run equilibrium output < potential GDP; cyclical unemployment exists. Self-correction: unemployment → wages fall → SRAS shifts right → output returns to potential (slow process). Policy intervention: expansionary fiscal (cut taxes, increase spending) or expansionary monetary (lower interest rates) shifts AD right — faster but risks inflation. Inflationary gap: short-run equilibrium output > potential GDP; economy overheating, inflation rising. Self-correction: tight labor market → wages rise → SRAS shifts left. Policy intervention: contractionary fiscal/monetary to shift AD left.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Fiscal Policy",[
      P("What is the difference between expansionary and contractionary fiscal policy?","Think government responses to economic conditions.","Expansionary fiscal policy: increase government spending and/or cut taxes → increase aggregate demand → offset recession. Contractionary fiscal policy: decrease government spending and/or raise taxes → decrease aggregate demand → reduce inflationary pressure. Automatic stabilizers: programs that automatically expand/contract with economy (unemployment insurance, progressive taxes) — built-in fiscal policy without legislative action. Crowding out: government borrowing competes with private borrowing → interest rates rise → private investment falls — partially offsets expansionary policy. Fiscal multiplier: $1 of government spending increases GDP by more than $1 (through spending rounds).","medium"),
      P("What is the national debt and what are the debates about its significance?","Think debt-to-GDP ratio.","National debt: accumulated federal deficits minus surpluses. Currently ~$30+ trillion; debt-to-GDP ratio ~120%. Concerns: (1) Interest payments crowd out other spending; (2) Future generations inherit obligation; (3) Possible sovereign debt crisis if creditors lose confidence. Counter-arguments: (1) Government can 'roll over' debt indefinitely if solvent; (2) Much debt held domestically (owe it to ourselves); (3) Low interest rates (historically) make borrowing cheap; (4) Counter-cyclical deficit spending may be optimal; (5) Debt-to-GDP matters more than absolute level. Debate: Modern Monetary Theory (deficits only matter if they cause inflation) vs. conventional view.","hard"),
      P("What is the Laffer Curve and what does it say about tax policy?","Think relationship between tax rates and revenue.","Laffer Curve: depicts relationship between tax rate and government revenue. At 0% rate: no revenue. At 100% rate: no incentive to work → no income → no revenue. Somewhere between: revenue maximized. Implication: cutting tax rates might increase revenue if current rate is above optimum (supply-side economics, 'trickle-down'). Evidence: Reagan tax cuts (1981) reduced revenues significantly; most economists believe US operates below peak — further cuts lose revenue. But in very high-tax regimes, cuts could plausibly increase revenue. The curve is theoretically valid; the debate is about where economies sit on it.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Monetary Policy",[
      P("What is the Federal Reserve and what tools does it use?","Think central bank functions.","Federal Reserve (Fed): US central bank; independent of direct political control. Dual mandate: maximum employment AND stable prices (2% inflation target). Tools: (1) Open market operations — buy/sell Treasury securities; buying increases bank reserves and money supply; selling decreases. (2) Federal funds rate target — rate banks charge each other for overnight loans; lowering stimulates, raising contracts economy. (3) Reserve requirements (rarely changed). (4) Discount rate — rate Fed charges banks for direct loans. Quantitative easing (QE): buying longer-term securities to lower long-term rates when short-term rates near zero.","medium"),
      P("What is the quantity theory of money?","Think MV = PQ.","Quantity Theory: MV = PQ. M = money supply, V = velocity of money (how often each dollar is spent per year), P = price level, Q = real output. If V and Q are relatively stable, increases in M lead to proportional increases in P — inflation is always and everywhere a monetary phenomenon (Friedman). Implication: central bank controls inflation by controlling money supply. Critique: V is not stable (especially in financial crises — liquidity trap); Q responds to monetary changes in short run. Basis for monetarism: steady, predictable money supply growth better than discretionary policy.","hard"),
      P("How does monetary policy transmission work?","Think mechanisms from Fed action to real economy.","Transmission channels: (1) Interest rate channel — Fed lowers fed funds rate → short-term rates fall → long-term rates follow → cheaper to borrow → more investment and consumption; (2) Asset price channel — lower rates → higher stock and bond prices → wealth effect → more spending; (3) Exchange rate channel — lower US rates → dollar depreciates → exports more competitive → net exports rise; (4) Credit channel — lower rates → banks more willing to lend → more credit available to households and firms. Time lags: monetary policy affects economy with 'long and variable lags' (6–18 months) — Fed must act before problems fully develop.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("International Trade and Finance",[
      P("What is comparative advantage and why does it support free trade?","Think Ricardo and gains from trade.","Comparative advantage (Ricardo): a country has comparative advantage in producing a good if its opportunity cost of production is lower than trading partners — even if it has absolute advantage in all goods, trade is beneficial. Example: US can produce both software and wheat more efficiently than Mexico, but if US has relatively larger advantage in software, US specializes in software, Mexico in wheat — both gain. Free trade allows global specialization → more total output. Critiques: (1) Distribution matters (workers in import-competing industries lose even if nation gains); (2) Assumes full employment; (3) Dynamic comparative advantage (infant industry protection).","hard"),
      P("What is the balance of payments and what are its components?","Think current account and capital account.","Balance of payments (BOP): record of all economic transactions between a country and the rest of the world. Current account: trade in goods (merchandise trade balance) + services + primary income (investment income, wages) + secondary income (transfers, remittances). Capital/financial account: investment flows — FDI, portfolio investment, loans. Reserve account: changes in official reserves. BOP must balance: current account deficit must be financed by capital/financial account surplus (borrowing or selling assets to foreigners). US has persistent current account deficit — financed by foreign capital inflows (foreigners willing to hold dollar-denominated assets).","hard"),
      P("What are exchange rates and what determines them?","Think supply and demand for currency.","Exchange rate: price of one currency in terms of another. Floating exchange rate: determined by supply and demand in foreign exchange market. Demand for dollars: foreigners buying US goods, services, assets. Supply of dollars: Americans buying foreign goods, services, assets. Dollar appreciates: US exports more expensive (less competitive) → exports fall; imports cheaper → imports rise → trade deficit worsens. Dollar depreciates: opposite effects → trade balance improves. PPP: exchange rates should equalize purchasing power across countries in long run. Factors shifting exchange rates: interest rate differentials, inflation differentials, economic growth, political stability.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Economic Growth",[
      P("What factors determine long-run economic growth?","Think production function inputs.","Long-run growth: expansion of productive capacity (LRAS shifts right). Determinants: (1) Physical capital accumulation — investment in machinery, infrastructure; (2) Human capital — education, training, health; (3) Natural resources — but not determinative (Japan, Singapore grow without; Nigeria, Venezuela resource-rich but poor); (4) Technology — total factor productivity (TFP) — most important driver of sustained growth (Solow growth model); (5) Institutions — rule of law, property rights, contract enforcement, low corruption; (6) Openness to trade. Solow residual: portion of growth unexplained by capital and labor accumulation — attributed to technology.","hard"),
    ]),
  ],
  # Unit 8 — AP Microeconomics
  [
    T("Supply and Demand",[
      P("What is the law of demand and what causes the demand curve to shift?","Think price vs. non-price factors.","Law of demand: ceteris paribus, as price rises, quantity demanded falls (downward slope). Reasons: substitution effect (higher price → consumers switch to alternatives) and income effect (higher price → real purchasing power falls → buy less). Curve shifts (vs. movement along curve) — TRIBE: Tastes/preferences, Related goods prices (substitutes and complements), Income, Buyers (population), Expectations. Substitute goods: rise in price of substitute → demand increases. Complement goods: rise in price of complement → demand decreases.","medium"),
      P("What is price elasticity of demand and why does it matter?","Think responsiveness of demand to price changes.","Price elasticity of demand (PED): % change in quantity demanded / % change in price. Elastic (|PED| > 1): quantity responds strongly to price changes — luxury goods, goods with many substitutes, goods where spending is large share of budget. Inelastic (|PED| < 1): quantity responds weakly — necessities, addictive goods, few substitutes, small share of budget. Unit elastic (|PED| = 1). Business application: elastic demand → price cut increases total revenue; inelastic demand → price increase increases total revenue. Government application: tax inelastic goods (cigarettes, gasoline) for revenue with less quantity reduction.","hard"),
      P("What is market equilibrium and how do markets respond to disequilibrium?","Think surplus and shortage.","Market equilibrium: price at which quantity supplied = quantity demanded — market clears. Above equilibrium price: quantity supplied > quantity demanded → surplus → downward pressure on price. Below equilibrium price: quantity demanded > quantity supplied → shortage → upward pressure on price. Markets 'clear' through price adjustment (flexible prices). Government intervention: price ceiling below equilibrium → shortage (rent control); price floor above equilibrium → surplus (minimum wage, agricultural price supports). Markets tend toward equilibrium as long as prices are free to adjust — this is the 'invisible hand.'","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Consumer and Producer Theory",[
      P("What is consumer surplus and producer surplus?","Think gains from trade.","Consumer surplus: difference between what consumers are willing to pay and what they actually pay — area above price, below demand curve. Producer surplus: difference between what producers receive and their minimum acceptable price — area below price, above supply curve. Total surplus = CS + PS — measures total welfare gains from trade in a market. At equilibrium: total surplus maximized (competitive market is efficient). Deadweight loss: reduction in total surplus due to underproduction or overproduction — created by taxes, price controls, monopoly.","medium"),
      P("What is the law of diminishing marginal utility?","Think satisfaction from additional consumption.","Marginal utility (MU): additional satisfaction from consuming one more unit. Law of diminishing marginal utility: as consumption increases, each additional unit provides less additional satisfaction (the first slice of pizza is more satisfying than the 10th). Consumer equilibrium: maximize utility by allocating spending so MU/Price is equal across all goods — spend the last dollar on each good to get equal marginal utility. Basis for downward-sloping demand: as price falls, buying more increases satisfaction until MU falls to equal lower price.","medium"),
      P("What is the production function and what is diminishing marginal product?","Think short-run production.","Production function: relationship between inputs and output. Short run: at least one input is fixed (capital); firm can only vary variable inputs (labor). Marginal product of labor (MPL): additional output from hiring one more worker. Diminishing marginal returns: as more variable input is added to fixed inputs, MPL eventually falls. Example: adding workers to fixed factory — first few workers very productive; eventually crowding and coordination reduce additional output per worker. Leads to upward-sloping marginal cost curve — as MPL falls, MC rises.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Costs and Revenues",[
      P("What is the difference between accounting profit and economic profit?","Think explicit vs. implicit costs.","Accounting profit: total revenue minus explicit (out-of-pocket) costs. Economic profit: total revenue minus all costs — explicit AND implicit (opportunity costs). Implicit costs: value of resources the firm owns and uses (owner's time, capital invested). Normal profit: zero economic profit — firm earning exactly what resources could earn in best alternative use. When economists say firms 'maximize profit' they mean economic profit; accounting profit overstates gains by excluding opportunity costs. Economic profit signals whether to enter or exit an industry.","medium"),
      P("What are economies and diseconomies of scale?","Think long-run average cost curve.","Economies of scale: as output increases, long-run average cost falls. Causes: specialization and division of labor, more efficient machinery, bulk purchasing, spreading fixed costs over more output. Diseconomies of scale: as output continues to increase, LRAC eventually rises. Causes: coordination problems, communication costs, bureaucracy, loss of managerial control. Constant returns to scale: LRAC stays flat. Minimum efficient scale (MES): lowest output at which LRAC is minimized — determines industry structure (MES relative to market size → monopoly, oligopoly, or competitive market).","hard"),
      P("What is the relationship between marginal cost and average cost?","Think the 'teaching assistant' relationship.","When MC < AC: AC is falling (each additional unit costs less than the average, pulling average down). When MC > AC: AC is rising. When MC = AC: AC is at its minimum. The MC curve always crosses the ATC and AVC curves at their minimum points. This is a mathematical relationship, not an economic law — like how a student's marginal GPA (this semester's grades) below their average pulls the average down; above pulls it up. Firms minimize average cost by producing where MC = ATC.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Market Structures",[
      P("What are the characteristics of perfect competition?","Think ideal competitive market.","Perfect competition: (1) Many buyers and sellers — no single firm has market power; (2) Homogeneous/identical product — no differentiation; (3) Free entry and exit — no barriers; (4) Perfect information; (5) Price takers — each firm accepts market price. Profit-maximizing rule: produce where P = MC (since P = MR for price taker). Long-run equilibrium: P = MC = ATC → zero economic profit (normal profit). Allocative efficiency (P = MC) and productive efficiency (P = ATC minimum) both achieved. Few real markets perfectly competitive — agriculture and commodity markets come closest.","medium"),
      P("What is monopoly and why is it inefficient?","Think market power and deadweight loss.","Monopoly: single seller with no close substitutes; significant barriers to entry (patents, economies of scale, control of resources, government franchise). Monopolist is price maker — faces downward-sloping demand. Profit maximization: MC = MR (but MR < P because monopolist must lower price on all units to sell more). Result: P > MC → allocative inefficiency; quantity below competitive equilibrium → deadweight loss. Monopolist earns economic profit in long run (barriers prevent entry). Regulation: price regulation (P = MC), antitrust enforcement, nationalization, taxation of monopoly profit.","hard"),
      P("What is oligopoly and what is the role of game theory?","Think strategic interdependence.","Oligopoly: few large firms; high barriers to entry; strategic interdependence — each firm's decisions affect and depend on rivals'. Models: kinked demand curve (explains price rigidity), Cournot (quantity competition), Bertrand (price competition), Stackelberg (leader-follower). Game theory: Prisoner's Dilemma shows why firms in oligopoly tend toward Nash Equilibrium even when it's not collectively optimal. Cartel: oligopolists collude to act like monopoly — illegal in US (Sherman Antitrust Act). OPEC: legal international cartel. Cartels unstable because each member has incentive to cheat (produce more than agreed quota).","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Factor Markets",[
      P("What is derived demand and how does it apply to labor markets?","Think demand for inputs.","Derived demand: demand for a factor of production derives from demand for the output it produces. Labor demand: firms hire workers to produce goods → labor demand depends on product market conditions. Marginal revenue product of labor (MRPL) = MPL × MR. Competitive firm: MR = P, so MRPL = MPL × P — the value of what the marginal worker produces. Labor demand curve: downward sloping — as more workers hired, MPL falls (diminishing returns) → MRPL falls → willing to pay less for additional workers. Shifts in labor demand: changes in product price, technology (complements vs. substitutes), prices of other factors.","hard"),
      P("What is the minimum wage and what are its economic effects?","Think price floor in labor market.","Minimum wage: legal price floor — sets minimum hourly rate above equilibrium for low-skill workers. Predicted effects: quantity of labor demanded falls; quantity supplied rises → unemployment (surplus of labor). Debate: Traditional model predicts unemployment; empirical evidence mixed — some studies find minimal employment effects. Explanations for small effects: (1) Monopsony (firms have market power in labor markets → would hire more at higher wage); (2) Efficiency wages (higher wages increase productivity and reduce turnover); (3) Demand stimulus (low-wage workers spend all income → increases demand). Current research: modest minimum wage increases may have minimal unemployment effects; large increases more likely to cause disemployment.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Market Failures and Government Intervention",[
      P("What is a public good and what is the free-rider problem?","Think non-rival and non-excludable.","Public good: (1) Non-rival — one person's use doesn't reduce availability for others (national defense); (2) Non-excludable — cannot prevent non-payers from benefiting. Free-rider problem: rational individuals won't pay for non-excludable goods (others will pay and they'll benefit anyway). Result: private market underprovides public goods. Solution: government provision funded by taxes. Club goods: non-rival but excludable (cable TV, national parks with fees). Common goods: rival but non-excludable → tragedy of the commons (fisheries, groundwater, congested highways).","medium"),
      P("What are externalities and how can they be corrected?","Think spillover effects.","Externality: cost or benefit imposed on third parties not part of a transaction. Negative externality (pollution): social cost > private cost → market overproduces → deadweight loss. Positive externality (education, vaccination): social benefit > private benefit → market underproduces. Corrections: Pigouvian tax (negative externality) — tax = external cost → internalizes externality → moves output toward social optimum. Subsidy (positive externality) — subsidy = external benefit. Coase theorem: if property rights are well-defined and transaction costs are low, parties will bargain to efficient outcome regardless of initial rights assignment.","hard"),
      P("What is price discrimination and when can a firm practice it?","Think charging different customers different prices.","Price discrimination: charging different prices to different consumers for the same good. Requirements: (1) Some market power (not perfectly competitive); (2) Ability to segment markets (identify different willingness-to-pay); (3) Ability to prevent resale (arbitrage). Types: 1st degree (perfect) — different price to each customer (car dealership bargaining); 2nd degree — different prices for different quantities (bulk discounts); 3rd degree — different prices to different groups (student discounts, senior discounts, international drug pricing). Effect: captures consumer surplus → increases producer surplus; may increase output beyond monopoly level → can actually reduce deadweight loss.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("International Trade",[
      P("How do tariffs affect domestic producers, consumers, and government revenue?","Think welfare analysis of trade protection.","Tariff: tax on imports. Effects: (1) Domestic producers protected — receive higher price → produce more → gain producer surplus; (2) Domestic consumers pay higher prices → buy less → lose consumer surplus; (3) Government gains tariff revenue; (4) Deadweight loss — efficient trade that would have occurred without tariff is lost. Net welfare effect: consumer loss > producer gain + government revenue → net welfare loss for the country imposing tariff. Exception: large country with market power — can improve terms of trade by reducing import demand → optimal tariff theory. But invites retaliation.","hard"),
    ]),
  ],
  # Unit 9 — AP Psychology
  [
    T("History and Approaches",[
      P("What are the major theoretical perspectives in psychology?","Think the seven main approaches.","Major perspectives: (1) Biological/neuroscience: behavior stems from genetics, brain chemistry, nervous system; (2) Psychoanalytic/psychodynamic: unconscious drives, early childhood experiences; (3) Behavioral: behavior shaped by learning (classical and operant conditioning); (4) Cognitive: mental processes — attention, memory, thinking; (5) Humanistic: conscious experience, free will, self-actualization (Maslow, Rogers); (6) Sociocultural: cultural and social influences on behavior; (7) Evolutionary: behavior reflects adaptations that enhanced reproductive success. Most contemporary psychologists adopt a biopsychosocial model — integrating biological, psychological, and social factors.","medium"),
      P("Who were the founders of psychology and what did they contribute?","Think Wundt, James, Freud, Watson, Skinner.","Wilhelm Wundt (1879): established first psychology lab in Leipzig; structuralism (analyzed conscious experience into elements via introspection). William James: functionalism (mental processes evolved to help organisms adapt; studied why, not just what). Freud: psychoanalytic theory; unconscious processes; id/ego/superego; psychosexual development. Watson: behaviorism (only observable behavior, not mental states, is proper subject of psychology). Skinner: operant conditioning; radical behaviorism; reinforcement schedules. Piaget: cognitive development stages. These founders shaped the field's major schools and debates that continue today.","medium"),
      P("What is the difference between nature and nurture and how is it studied?","Think genetics vs. environment and twin studies.","Nature: genetic, biological influences on behavior. Nurture: environmental, experiential influences. Not an either/or — virtually all traits reflect gene-environment interaction (nature VIA nurture). Research methods: twin studies (identical vs. fraternal twins compare genetic vs. environmental contributions); adoption studies; family studies. Heritability: proportion of variation in a trait explained by genetic variation — applies to populations, not individuals. Key finding: heritability of personality, intelligence, and most traits is substantial (40–80%) — but environment shapes how genes express. Epigenetics: environmental factors can change gene expression without changing DNA sequence.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Research Methods",[
      P("What is the difference between correlation and causation?","Think why correlation doesn't prove causation.","Correlation: statistical relationship between two variables — as one changes, the other tends to change. Doesn't establish causation because of: (1) Directionality problem — which variable caused which? (2) Third variable problem — a third unmeasured variable may cause both. Example: ice cream sales correlate with drowning deaths — summer (third variable) causes both. Establishing causation requires: experiment with random assignment. Correlations described by coefficient (r) — ranges -1 to +1; direction (positive/negative); strength (closer to ±1 = stronger).","medium"),
      P("What is an experiment and why is random assignment important?","Think experimental control.","Experiment: researcher manipulates independent variable (IV), controls other variables, measures dependent variable (DV) to establish causation. Control group: doesn't receive treatment (or receives placebo). Experimental group: receives treatment. Random assignment: each participant has equal chance of being in either group — equates groups on all variables (known and unknown), so any outcome difference can be attributed to the IV. Without random assignment: confounding variables undermine causal conclusions. Double-blind: neither participants nor researchers know who's in which group — prevents placebo effects and researcher bias from contaminating results.","medium"),
      P("What are the major ethical principles in psychological research?","Think APA ethical guidelines.","APA ethical principles: (1) Informed consent — participants must voluntarily agree to participate knowing what's involved; (2) Confidentiality — data protected; (3) Debriefing — after deception studies, participants must be fully informed; (4) Protection from harm — minimize physical and psychological risks; (5) Right to withdraw — participants can leave at any time without penalty. Famous ethical violations: Milgram obedience experiments (not fully debriefed about deception); Stanford Prison Experiment (Abu Ghraib-level abuse, study ended early). IRBs (Institutional Review Boards) review all human research for ethical compliance.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Biological Bases of Behavior",[
      P("What are the major structures of the brain and their functions?","Think lobes, limbic system, and brainstem.","Major structures: Brainstem (medulla oblongata, pons, reticular formation): regulates basic survival functions — breathing, heart rate, sleep. Cerebellum: coordination, balance, procedural memory. Limbic system: amygdala (fear, emotion), hippocampus (memory formation), hypothalamus (drives — hunger, sex, thirst; links nervous and endocrine systems). Cerebral cortex (lobes): frontal (executive function, personality, planning); parietal (sensory integration, spatial awareness); occipital (vision); temporal (hearing, language, face recognition). Left hemisphere: language (Broca's, Wernicke's areas); Right: spatial processing, emotion recognition.","medium"),
      P("How do neurons communicate?","Think action potential and synaptic transmission.","Neuron communication: Resting potential: inside neuron negatively charged (-70mV). Action potential: electrical signal — depolarization wave travels down axon when threshold reached; all-or-nothing law. Synaptic transmission: action potential reaches terminal → vesicles release neurotransmitters → cross synapse → bind to receptor sites on postsynaptic neuron → excitatory (EPSP) or inhibitory (IPSP). Reuptake: neurotransmitter reabsorbed by sending neuron. Key NTs: dopamine (reward, movement), serotonin (mood, sleep), acetylcholine (muscle activation, memory), norepinephrine (arousal), GABA (inhibition), glutamate (excitation).","hard"),
      P("What is the difference between the sympathetic and parasympathetic nervous systems?","Think fight-or-flight vs. rest-and-digest.","Autonomic nervous system: controls involuntary bodily functions. Sympathetic: activates during stress/danger — dilates pupils, accelerates heart rate, inhibits digestion, releases adrenaline, prepares for action ('fight-or-flight'). Parasympathetic: dominates during rest — constricts pupils, slows heart rate, stimulates digestion, conserves energy ('rest-and-digest'). The two systems generally work in opposition. Chronic stress: sympathetic activation without recovery → health consequences (cardiovascular, immune system). Biofeedback: learn to control physiological arousal by monitoring and consciously regulating autonomic responses.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Sensation and Perception",[
      P("What is the difference between sensation and perception?","Think data collection vs. interpretation.","Sensation: process of detecting physical energy (photons, sound waves, chemicals) through sensory receptors and converting to neural signals — transduction. Perception: process of organizing and interpreting sensory signals — giving them meaning. Same sensation, different perceptions: optical illusions; cross-cultural differences in color perception; context effects. Top-down processing: prior knowledge, expectations, context shape perception. Bottom-up processing: perception built from raw sensory data. Perceptual set: mental predisposition shapes what we perceive — we see what we expect to see.","medium"),
      P("What are the Gestalt principles of perceptual organization?","Think figure-ground and grouping.","Gestalt principles: the whole is different from the sum of its parts — we perceive organized patterns, not just collections of sensations. Principles: (1) Figure-ground — perceive objects against background; (2) Proximity — elements close together perceived as group; (3) Similarity — similar elements grouped; (4) Continuity — prefer smooth, continuous patterns; (5) Closure — complete incomplete figures; (6) Connectedness — linked elements perceived as unit. Developed by German psychologists (Wertheimer, Kohler, Koffka) as critique of structuralism's atomism — perception is constructive, not merely additive.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("States of Consciousness",[
      P("What are the stages of sleep and why is sleep important?","Think NREM and REM.","Sleep stages: NREM 1 (light sleep, hypnic jerks), NREM 2 (sleep spindles, K-complexes), NREM 3 (deep slow-wave sleep — restoration, growth hormone), REM (rapid eye movement — dreaming, brain active, muscles paralyzed). 90-minute cycle repeats; more NREM early, more REM later. Functions of sleep: memory consolidation (hippocampus replays experiences during NREM), neural restoration, immune function, emotional regulation. Sleep deprivation: cognitive impairment (equivalent to alcohol intoxication), emotional dysregulation, metabolic effects. Disorders: insomnia, sleep apnea, narcolepsy, REM sleep behavior disorder.","medium"),
      P("What are the major theories of dreaming?","Think Freud, activation-synthesis, and consolidation.","Dream theories: (1) Freud: dreams are disguised wish fulfillment — manifest content (story) conceals latent content (unconscious desires); little empirical support today. (2) Activation-synthesis (Hobson): REM activates random neural signals; cortex synthesizes into coherent narrative — no deep meaning. (3) Memory consolidation: dreams replay and consolidate waking experiences — strong evidence; REM sleep essential for learning and memory. (4) Threat simulation: evolutionary theory — dreams rehearse threatening scenarios to prepare responses. Dreams occur mainly in REM; vivid, emotional, narrative. Content: mostly negative emotions (anxiety, fear) with some positive.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Learning",[
      P("What is classical conditioning and what are its key concepts?","Think Pavlov.","Classical conditioning (Pavlov): learning through association — neutral stimulus becomes conditioned stimulus by being paired with unconditioned stimulus. Key terms: US (unconditioned stimulus — naturally causes response; meat), UR (unconditioned response — automatic response to US; salivation), CS (conditioned stimulus — previously neutral; bell), CR (conditioned response — learned response to CS; salivation). Acquisition: CS-US pairing. Extinction: CS presented without US → CR weakens. Spontaneous recovery: extinguished CR reappears after rest. Generalization: similar stimuli elicit CR. Discrimination: respond to CS but not similar stimuli. Application: phobias (fear response conditioned), Little Albert experiment.","medium"),
      P("What is operant conditioning and what are the schedules of reinforcement?","Think Skinner.","Operant conditioning (Skinner): learning through consequences — behavior increases when reinforced, decreases when punished. Positive reinforcement: add pleasant stimulus. Negative reinforcement: remove unpleasant stimulus (both increase behavior). Positive punishment: add unpleasant stimulus (decreases behavior). Negative punishment: remove pleasant stimulus (decreases behavior). Reinforcement schedules: fixed ratio (every nth response — fast, steady responding; pause after reinforcement); variable ratio (unpredictable; slot machine — highest, most resistant to extinction); fixed interval (first response after time period); variable interval (unpredictable time; most resistant). Shaping: reinforce successive approximations to target behavior.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Cognition",[
      P("What are the main components of memory?","Think encoding, storage, retrieval and multi-store model.","Memory model: Encoding (getting information in) → Storage (retaining) → Retrieval (getting out). Multi-store: Sensory memory (brief, modality-specific; iconic ~0.5sec, echoic ~3–4sec) → Short-term/working memory (limited capacity ~7±2 items; ~20 seconds without rehearsal; active processing) → Long-term memory (unlimited capacity, long duration). LTM types: explicit/declarative (conscious) — episodic (personal events) and semantic (facts, concepts); implicit/procedural (skills, habits — independent of hippocampus). Hippocampus: critical for forming explicit LTM (HM patient — couldn't form new declarative memories).","medium"),
      P("What is the availability heuristic and how does it lead to biases?","Think ease of recall as a proxy for frequency.","Availability heuristic: judging probability or frequency by how easily examples come to mind. Leads to biases: (1) Overestimate risk of dramatic, vivid events (plane crashes, shark attacks) vs. mundane ones (car accidents, heart disease) — media coverage makes vivid events easily available; (2) Overweight recent events; (3) Overestimate prevalence of conditions you've just learned about (medical students' disease). Kahneman (System 1 thinking): fast, automatic, heuristic-based reasoning feels right but is prone to systematic errors. Awareness of heuristics doesn't fully eliminate their effects.","medium"),
      P("What is language and how do children acquire it?","Think critical period and nativist vs. learning theory.","Language: system of symbols and rules for combining them to communicate. Chomsky's nativist theory: Language Acquisition Device (LAD) — innate biological capacity; universal grammar explains rapid acquisition; child couldn't learn language so fast through reinforcement alone (poverty of stimulus argument). Critical period: first 7 years; after puberty much harder to learn native-level language (Genie case). Behaviorist view: imitation and reinforcement. Current consensus: both nature (biological readiness, universal grammar features) and nurture (language exposure, interaction) essential. Stages: cooing, babbling, one-word (holophrases), two-word, full sentences.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Motivation and Emotion",[
      P("What is Maslow's hierarchy of needs?","Think pyramid of motivation.","Maslow's hierarchy (1943): five levels of human needs; lower needs must be met before higher needs motivate behavior. (1) Physiological: food, water, sleep, shelter; (2) Safety: security, stability, freedom from fear; (3) Love/belonging: relationships, community, intimacy; (4) Esteem: achievement, recognition, status; (5) Self-actualization: realizing full potential, peak experiences. Critique: hierarchy is culturally specific (Western individualism); starving artists pursue self-actualization; some people prioritize esteem over safety. Self-transcendence: Maslow later added level above self-actualization — meaning, spiritual experience.","easy"),
      P("What are the major theories of emotion?","Think James-Lange, Cannon-Bard, Schachter-Singer.","Emotion theories: James-Lange: physiological arousal comes first → we interpret it as emotion ('I am afraid because I tremble'). Cannon-Bard: physiological arousal and emotional experience occur simultaneously and independently. Schachter-Singer (two-factor): arousal + cognitive label = emotion; arousal is non-specific, we label it based on context (misattribution of arousal — bridge study). Facial feedback hypothesis: facial expressions cause emotions (Duchenne smile → genuinely feel happier). Lazarus: cognitive appraisal precedes emotion — we evaluate whether situation is threatening or not. Ekman: 6 universal basic emotions (fear, anger, disgust, happiness, sadness, surprise) recognized across cultures.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Personality",[
      P("What are the major theories of personality?","Think Freud, trait theories, and humanistic.","Major theories: Freud's psychoanalytic: personality structured as id (instinctual drives, pleasure principle), ego (mediates between id and reality), superego (internalized moral standards); defense mechanisms protect ego; psychosexual stages. Humanistic: Rogers (unconditional positive regard, self-concept, congruence), Maslow (self-actualization). Trait theories: Allport (individual traits); Big Five (OCEAN): Openness, Conscientiousness, Extraversion, Agreeableness, Neuroticism — most empirically supported; stable across cultures. Social cognitive: Bandura — self-efficacy; reciprocal determinism (person, behavior, environment all influence each other).","medium"),
      P("What is the Big Five personality model?","Think OCEAN.","Big Five (OCEAN): most empirically validated personality model. Openness to experience: curiosity, creativity, appreciation of art and new ideas — high in artists and intellectuals. Conscientiousness: organization, self-discipline, goal-directedness — strongest predictor of academic and occupational success. Extraversion: sociability, positive emotion, assertiveness. Agreeableness: cooperation, trust, empathy — high in caregivers. Neuroticism: emotional instability, anxiety, depression. Traits: heritable (~50%); stable across situations and lifespan (though personality matures — conscientiousness and agreeableness increase with age); predictive of life outcomes (health, relationships, career).","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Psychological Disorders and Treatment",[
      P("What is the DSM-5 and how does it classify psychological disorders?","Think diagnostic categories.","DSM-5 (Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, 5th ed., 2013): APA's classification system for psychological disorders. Categorical approach: disorders defined by criteria (symptoms, duration, impairment). Major categories: anxiety disorders (GAD, panic disorder, social anxiety, phobias, OCD, PTSD); depressive disorders (MDD, persistent depressive disorder); bipolar disorders; schizophrenia spectrum; personality disorders; neurodevelopmental disorders (ADHD, autism spectrum); substance use disorders. Limitations: high comorbidity (many people have multiple diagnoses); cultural variation in expression; medical model criticized (pathologizes normal variation). Research: NIMH's RDoC framework — biologically based dimensional approach.","medium"),
      P("What are the main psychological therapies and what are they based on?","Think CBT, psychoanalytic, humanistic.","Psychoanalysis (Freud): bring unconscious conflicts to consciousness through free association, dream analysis, transference interpretation. Long, expensive; limited evidence. Humanistic (Rogers): client-centered therapy; unconditional positive regard, empathy, genuineness → client's self-actualization. Behavioral therapy: extinguish maladaptive behaviors through conditioning (systematic desensitization for phobias, exposure therapy). Cognitive therapy (Beck): identify and challenge distorted thinking patterns. CBT: combines cognitive and behavioral — most evidence-supported; effective for depression, anxiety, PTSD. Group, family, and couples therapy. Meta-analyses: most therapies more effective than no treatment; CBT consistently effective across disorders.","hard"),
      P("What are antidepressants and how do they work?","Think SSRIs and mechanism.","Antidepressants: SSRIs (selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors) — most widely prescribed (fluoxetine/Prozac, sertraline/Zoloft); block reuptake of serotonin → more serotonin available in synapse. SNRIs: block both serotonin and norepinephrine reuptake. MAOIs (older): block enzyme that breaks down monoamines; effective but dangerous interactions. Tricyclics (older): broad mechanism; more side effects. Effectiveness: antidepressants work better than placebo for moderate-severe depression; comparable to therapy; combination most effective. Controversy: Kirsch meta-analysis argued placebo effect accounts for most benefit in mild-moderate depression. Takes 2–6 weeks for full effect.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Social Psychology",[
      P("What is the fundamental attribution error?","Think dispositional vs. situational explanations.","Fundamental attribution error (FAE): tendency to overestimate dispositional (personal, internal) factors and underestimate situational factors when explaining others' behavior. Example: someone cuts you off in traffic → 'they're a jerk' (disposition) rather than 'they may be rushing to the hospital' (situation). Actor-observer bias: we attribute others' behavior to disposition but our own behavior to situation ('I was late because of traffic; they were late because they're irresponsible'). Cultural variation: FAE stronger in individualistic cultures (US, Western Europe) than collectivistic (East Asia) — context vs. individual attribution.","medium"),
      P("What did the Milgram obedience studies demonstrate?","Think authority and ordinary evil.","Milgram's experiment (1961–62): 'teacher' (participant) administered what they believed were increasingly severe electric shocks to 'learner' (confederate) when they made errors, at instruction of experimenter in lab coat. 65% of participants continued to maximum (450V) despite hearing screams; no one stopped before 300V. Implications: ordinary people can commit great harm when obedient to legitimate authority in structured situation; situational forces overpower character (contradicts dispositional assumptions). Context: post-Holocaust, Eichmann trial ('just following orders'). Critiques: ethical (deception, stress); external validity (would real-world obedience be this high?).","hard"),
      P("What is conformity and what does Asch's research show?","Think social influence.","Conformity: adjusting behavior or beliefs to match group norms. Asch's line experiment: participants gave obviously wrong answers about line length to match group of confederates — 75% conformed at least once. Why conform: normative social influence (want to be liked, accepted — go along even when know group is wrong) vs. informational social influence (genuinely believe group has better information). Conformity increases with: group unanimity (one dissenter dramatically reduces conformity), perceived group expertise, public (vs. private) response, collectivist culture. Minority influence: consistent minority can change majority over time (Moscovici) — different from conformity process.","medium"),
    ]),
  ]
]
